\b0 Sometime in mid-1969, Doubleday called me up to ask if I would write a science fiction story that could serve as the basis of a movie. I didn\rquote t want to, because I don\rquote t like to get tangled up with the visual media directly. They\rquote ve got money, but that\rquote s all they\rquote ve got. But Doubleday pressed me and I don\rquote t like to refuse Doubleday. I agreed. \par
\tab Then eventually I had dinner with a very pleasant gentleman who was involved with the motion picture company and who wanted to discuss the story with me. \par
\tab He told me he wanted an undersea setting and that suited me. He then went on to describe with considerable enthusiasm the nature of the characters he wanted in the story, and the events he thought would be necessary. As he spoke, my spirits sank. The fact was that I didn\rquote t want the hero he described; I didn\rquote t want, with even greater intensity, the heroine he described; and most of all, I didn\rquote t want the events he described. \par
\tab I have always found myself unable, however, to express a negative reaction to people, especially face to face. I did my best to smile and act interested. \par
\tab The next day I called up Doubleday. It might not be too late. I asked if the contract had been signed. Yes, indeed, it had, and a large advance had been paid over, of which most was to be turned over to me. \par
\tab I didn\rquote t think there was room for my spirits to sink lower, but they did. I \i had \i0 to write the story. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then,\rdblquote  I said, \ldblquote if what I write is not acceptable, would you return the advance?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We don\rquote t have to,\rdblquote  I was told. \ldblquote The advance is unconditional. If they don\rquote t like your story, we still keep the advance.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  I said. \ldblquote I don\rquote t want it that way. If what I do is unacceptable, I want the entire advance returned. Take your share of it out of my royalties.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Doubleday doesn\rquote t like to refuse me anything either, so they agreed, although they made it plain they would return their share and not take anything out of my royalties. \par
\tab That meant I was under no obligation to do anything but my best, as I conceived that best to be. On September 1, 1969, I began to write WATERCLAP and I did it my way. I knew exactly what the movie people wanted and I didn\rquote t give it to them. Naturally, they rejected it when it was done and every cent they had advanced was returned to them. \par
\tab This was a huge relief to me, you can well imagine. \par
\tab And there is a world outside Hollywood, too. Ejler Jakobsson of \i Galaxy \i0 liked the story as I had written it, so it appeared in the May 1970 issue of that magazine. He paid me far less than the movie people would have, but then, all he bought was the story. \par
