\b0\tab Stephen Demerest looked at the textured sky. He kept looking at it and found the blue opaque and revolting. \par
\tab Unwarily, he had looked at the Sun, for there was nothing to blank it out automatically, and then he had snatched his eyes away in panic. He wasn\rquote t blinded; just a few afterimages. Even the Sun was washed out. \par
\tab Involuntarily, he thought of Ajax\rquote s prayer in Homer\rquote s \i Iliad. \i0 They were fighting over the body of Patroclus in the mist and Ajax said, \ldblquote O Father Zeus, save the Achaeans out of this mist! Make the sky clean, grant us to see with our eyes! Kill us in the light, since it is thy pleasure to kill us!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest thought: Kill us in the light--\par
\tab Kill us in the clear light on the Moon, where the sky is black and soft, where the stars shine brightly, where the cleanliness and purity of vacuum make all things sharp. \par
\tab --Not in this low-clinging, fuzzy blue. \par
\tab He shuddered. It was an actual physical shudder that shook his lanky body, and he was annoyed. He was going to die. He was sure of it. And it wouldn\rquote t be under the blue, either, come to think of it, but under the black--but a different black. \par
\tab It was as though in answer to that thought that the ferry pilot, short, swarthy, crisp-haired, came up .to him and said, \ldblquote Ready for the black, Mr. Demerest?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest nodded. He towered over the other as he did over most of the men of Earth. They were thick, all of them, and took their short, low steps with ease. He himself had to feel his footsteps, guide them through the air; even the impalpable bond that held him to the ground was textured. \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m ready,\rdblquote  he said. He took a deep breath and deliberately repeated his earlier glance at the Sun. It was low in the morning sky, washed out by dusty air, and he knew it wouldn\rquote t blind him. He didn\rquote t think he would ever see it again. \par
\tab He had never seen a bathyscaphe before. Despite everything, he tended to think of it in terms of prototypes, an oblong balloon with a spherical gondola beneath. It was as though he persisted in thinking of space flight in terms of tons of fuel spewed backward in fire, and an irregular module feeling its way, spiderlike, toward the Lunar surface. \par
\tab The bathyscaphe was not like the image in his thoughts at all. Under its skin, it might still be buoyant bag and gondola, but it was all engineered sleekness now. \par
\tab\ldblquote My name is Javan,\rdblquote  said the ferry pilot. \ldblquote Omar Javan.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Javan?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Queer name to you? I\rquote m Iranian by descent; Earthman by persuasion. Once you get down there, there are no nationalities.\rdblquote  He grinned and his complexion grew darker against the even whiteness of his teeth. \ldblquote If you don\rquote t mind, we\rquote ll be starting in a minute. You\rquote ll be my only passenger, so I guess you carry weight.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Demerest dryly. \ldblquote At least a hundred pounds more than I\rquote m used to.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re from the Moon? I thought you had a queer walk on you. I hope it\rquote s not uncomfortable.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s not exactly comfortable, ,but I manage. We exercise for this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, come on board.\rdblquote  He stood aside and let Demerest walk down the gangplank. \ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t go to the Moon myself.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You go to Ocean-Deep.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote About fifty times so far. That\rquote s different.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest got on board. It was cramped, but he didn\rquote t mind that. It might be a space module except that it was more--well, textured. There was that word again. There was the clear feeling everywhere that mass didn\rquote t matter. Mass was held up; it didn\rquote t have to be hurled up. \par
\tab They were still on the surface. The blue sky could be seen greenishly through the clear thick glass. Javan said, \ldblquote You don\rquote t have to be strapped in. There\rquote s no acceleration. Smooth as oil, the whole thing. It won\rquote t take long; just about an hour. You can\rquote t smoke.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t smoke,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \par
\tab\ldblquote I hope you don\rquote t have claustrophobia.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Moon-men don\rquote t have claustrophobia.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All that open--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not in our cavern. We live in a\rdblquote --he groped for the phrase --\rdblquote a Lunar-Deep, a hundred feet deep.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A hundred feet!\rdblquote  The pilot seemed amused, but he didn\rquote t smile. \ldblquote We\rquote re slipping down now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The interior of the gondola was fitted into angles but here and there a section of wall beyond the instruments showed its basic sphericity. To Javan, the instruments seemed to be an extension of his arms; his eyes and hands moved over them lightly, almost lovingly. \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re all checked out,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote but I like a last-minute look-over; we\rquote ll be facing a thousand atmospheres down there.\rdblquote  His finger touched a contact, and the round door closed massively inward and pressed against the beveled rim it met. \par
\tab\ldblquote The higher the pressure, the tighter that will hold,\rdblquote  said Javan. \ldblquote Take your last look at sunlight, Mr. Demerest.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The light still shone through the thick glass of the window. It was wavering now; there was water between the Sun and them now. \par
\tab\ldblquote The last look?\rdblquote  said Demerest. \par
\tab Javan snickered. \ldblquote Not the \i last \i0 look. I mean for the trip. ...I suppose you\rquote ve never been, on a bathyscaphe before.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, I haven\rquote t. Have many?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very few,\rdblquote  admitted Javan. \ldblquote But don\rquote t worry. It\rquote s just an underwater balloon. We\rquote ve introduced a million improvements since the first bathyscaphe. It\rquote s nuclear-powered now and we can move freely by water jet up to certain limits, but cut it down to basics and it\rquote s still a spherical gondola under buoyancy tanks. And it\rquote s still towed out to sea by a mother ship because it needs what power it carries too badly to waste it on surface travel. Ready?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ready.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The supporting cable of the mother ship flicked away and the bathyscaphe settled lower; then lower still, as sea water fed into the buoyancy tanks. For a few moments, caught in surface currents, it swayed, and then there was nothing. The bathyscaphe sank slowly through a deepening green. \par
\tab Javan relaxed. He said, \ldblquote John Bergen is head of Ocean-Deep. You\rquote re going to see him?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s a nice guy. His wife\rquote s with him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She is?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, sure. They have women down there. There\rquote s a bunch down there, fifty people. \ldblquote Some stay for months.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest put his finger on the narrow, nearly invisible seam where door met wall. He took it away and looked at it. He said, \ldblquote It\rquote s oily.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Silicone, really. The pressure squeezes some out. It\rquote s supposed to. ...Don\rquote t worry. Everything\rquote s automatic. Everything\rquote s fail-safe. The first sign of malfunction, any malfunction at all, our ballast is released and up we go.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You mean nothing\rquote s ever happened to these bathyscaphes?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What can happen?\rdblquote  The pilot looked sideways at his passenger. \ldblquote Once you get too deep for sperm whales, nothing can go wrong.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Sperm whales?\rdblquote  Demerest\rquote s thin face creased in a frown. \par
\tab\ldblquote Sure, they dive as deep as half a mile. If they hit a bathyscaphe--well, the walls of the buoyancy chambers aren\rquote t particularly strong. They don\rquote t have to be, you know. They\rquote re open to the sea and when the gasoline, which supplies the buoyancy, compresses, sea water enters.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was dark now. Demerest found his gaze fastened to the viewport. It was light inside the gondola, but it was dark in that window. And it was not the darkness of space; it was a thick darkness. \par
\tab Demerest said sharply, \ldblquote Let\rquote s get this straight, Mr. Javan. You are not equipped to withstand the attack of a sperm whale. Presumably you are not equipped to withstand the attack of a giant squid. Have there been any actual incidents of that sort?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s like this--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No games, please, and don\rquote t try ragging the greenhorn. I am asking out of professional curiosity. I am head safety engineer at Luna City and I am asking what precautions this bathyscaphe can take against possible collision with large creatures.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Javan looked embarrassed. He muttered, \ldblquote Actually, there have been no incidents.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are any expected? Even as a remote possibility?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Anything is remotely possible. But actually sperm whales are too intelligent to monkey with us and giant squid are too shy.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Can they see us?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, of course. We\rquote re lit up.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you have floodlights?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re already past the large-animal range, but we have them, and I\rquote ll turn them on for you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Through the black of the window there suddenly appeared a snow-storm, an inverted upward-falling snowstorm. The blackness had come alive with stars in three-dimensional array and all moving upward. \par
\tab Demerest said, \ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Just crud. Organic matter. Small creatures. They float, don\rquote t move much, and they catch the light. We\rquote re going down past them. They seem to be going up in consequence.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest\rquote s sense of perspective adjusted itself and he said, \ldblquote Aren\rquote t we dropping too quickly?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, we\rquote re not. If we were, I could use the nuclear engines, if I wanted to waste power; or I could drop some ballast. I\rquote ll be doing that later, but for now everything is fine. Relax, Mr. Demerest. The snow thins as we dive and we\rquote re not likely to see much in the way of spectacular life forms. There are small angler fish and such but they avoid us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest said, \ldblquote How many do you take down at a time?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve had as many as four passengers in this gondola, but that\rquote s crowded. We can put two bathyscaphes in tandem and carry ten, but that\rquote s clumsy. What we really need are trains of gondolas, heavier on the nukes-the nuclear engines-and lighter on the buoyancy. Stuff like that is on the drawing board, they tell me. Of course, they\rquote ve been telling me that for years.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There are plans for large-scale expansion of Ocean-Deep, then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Sure, why not? We\rquote ve got cities on the continental shelves, why not on the deep-sea bottom? The way I look at it, Mr. Demerest, where man can go, he will go and he should go. The Earth is ours to populate and we will populate it. All we need to make the deep sea habitable are completely maneuverable \lquote scaphes. The buoyancy chambers slow us, weaken us, and complicate the engineering.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But they also save you, don\rquote t they? If everything goes wrong at once, the gasoline you carry will still float you to the surface-. What would do that for you if your nuclear engines go wrong and you had no buoyancy?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If it comes to that, you can\rquote t expect to eliminate the chances of accident altogether, not even fatal ones.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know that very well,\rdblquote  said Demerest feelingly. \par
\tab Javan stiffened. The tone of his voice changed. \ldblquote Sorry. Didn\rquote t mean anything by that. Tough about that accident.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Demerest. Fifteen men and five women had died. One of the individuals listed among the \ldblquote men \ldblquote  had been fourteen years old. It had been pinned down to human failure. What could a head safety engineer say after that? \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab A pall dropped between the two men, a pall as thick and as turgid as the pressurized sea water outside. How could one allow for panic and for distraction and for depression all at once? There were the Moon-Blues--stupid name--but they struck men at inconvenient times. It wasn\rquote t always noticeable when the Moon-Blues came but it made men torpid and slow to react. \par
\tab How many times had a meteorite come along and been averted or smothered or successfully absorbed? How many times had a Moonquake done damage and been held in check? How many times had human failure been backed up and compensated for? How many times had accidents \i not \i0 happened? \par
\tab But you don\rquote t payoff on accidents not happening. There were twenty dead--\par
\par
\tab Javan said (how many long minutes later?), \ldblquote There are the lights of Ocean-Deep!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest could not make them out at first. He didn\rquote t know where to look. Twice before, luminescent creatures had flicked past the windows at a distance and with the floodlights off again, Demerest had thought them the first sign of Ocean-Deep. Now he saw nothing. \par
\tab\ldblquote Down there,\rdblquote  said Javan, without pointing. He was busy now, slowing the drop and edging the \lquote scaphe sideways. \par
\tab Demerest could hear the distant sighing of the water jets, steam-driven, with the steam formed by the heat of momentary bursts of fusion power. \par
\tab Demerest thought dimly: Deuterium is their fuel and it\rquote s all around them. Water is their exhaust and it\rquote s all around them. \par
\tab Javan was dropping some of his ballast, too, and began a kind of distant chatter. \ldblquote The ballast used to be steel pellets and they were dropped by electromagnetic controls. Anywhere up to fifty tons of it were used in each trip. Conservationists worried about spreading rusting steel over the ocean floor, so we switched to metal nodules that are dredged up from the continental shelf. We put a thin layer of iron over them so they can still be electromagnetically handled and the ocean bottom gets nothing that wasn\rquote t sub-ocean to begin with. Cheaper, too. ...But when we get out real nuclear \lquote scaphes, we won\rquote t need ballast at all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest scarcely heard him. Ocean-Deep could be seen now. Javan had turned on the floodlights and far below was the muddy floor of the Puerto Rican Trench. Resting on that floor like a cluster of equally muddy pearls was the spherical conglomerate of Ocean-Deep. \par
\tab Each unit was a sphere such as the one in which Demerest was now sinking toward contact, but much larger, and as Ocean-Deep expanded--expanded--expanded, new spheres were added. \par
\tab Demerest thought: They\rquote re only five and a half miles from home, not a quarter of a million. \par
\par
\tab\ldblquote How are we going to get through?\rdblquote  asked Demerest. \par
\tab The \lquote scaphe had made contact. Demerest heard the dull sound of metal against metal but then for minutes there had been nothing more than a kind of occasional scrape as Javan bent over his instruments in rapt concentration. \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry about that,\rdblquote  Javan said at last, in belated answer. \ldblquote There\rquote s no problem. The delay now is only because I have to make sure we fit tightly. There\rquote s an electromagnet joint that holds at every point of a perfect circle. When the instruments read correctly, that means we fit over the entrance door.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Which then opens?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It would if there were air on the other side, but there isn\rquote t. There\rquote s sea water, and that has to be driven out. \i Then \i0 we enter.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest did not miss this point. He had come here on this, the last day of his life, to give that same life meaning and he intended to miss nothing. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Why the added step? Why not keep the air lock, if that\rquote s what it is, a real air lock, and have air in it at an times?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote They tell me it\rquote s a matter of safety,\rdblquote  said Javan. \i\ldblquote Your \i0 specialty. The interface has equal pressure on both sides at all times, \i except \i0 when men are moving across. This door is the weakest point of the whole system, because it opens and closes; it has joints; it has seams. You know what I mean?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I do,\rdblquote  murmured Demerest. There was a logical flaw here and that meant there was a possible chink through which--but later. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Why are we waiting now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The lock is being emptied. The water is being forced out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By air.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Hell, no. They can\rquote t afford to waste air like that. It would take a thousand atmospheres to empty the chamber of its water, and filling the chamber with air at that density, even temporarily, is more air than they can afford to expend. Steam is what does it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of course. Yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Javan said cheerfully, \ldblquote You heat the water. No pressure in the world can stop water from turning to steam at a temperature of more than 374\'b0 C. And the steam forces the sea water out through a one-way valve.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Another weak point,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \ldblquote I suppose so. It\rquote s never failed yet. The water in the lock is being pushed out now. When hot steam starts bubbling out the valve, the process automatically stops and the lock is fun of overheated steam.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And then we have a whole ocean to cool it with. The temperature drops and the steam condenses. Once that happens, ordinary air can be let in at a pressure of one atmosphere and \i then \i0 the door opens.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How long must we wait?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not long. If there were anything wrong, there\rquote d be sirens sounding. At least, so they say. I never heard one in action.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was silence for a few minutes, and then there was a sudden sharp clap and a simultaneous jerk. \par
\tab Javan said, \ldblquote Sorry, I should have warned you. I\rquote m so used to it I forgot. When the door opens, a thousand atmospheres of pressure on the other side forces us hard against the metal of Ocean-Deep. No electromagnetic force can hold us hard enough to prevent that last hundredth-of-an-inch slam.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest unclenched his fist and released his breath. He said, \ldblquote Is everything all right?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The walls didn\rquote t crack, if that\rquote s what you mean. It sounds like doom, though, doesn\rquote t it? It sounds even worse when I\rquote ve got to leave and the air lock fills up again. Be prepared for that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab But Demerest was suddenly weary. Let\rquote s get on with it, he thought. I don\rquote t want to drag it out. He said, \ldblquote Do we go through now?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We go through.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The opening in the \lquote scaphe wall was round and small; even smaller than the one through which they had originally entered. Javan went through it sinuously, muttering that it always made him feel like a cork in a bottle. \par
\tab Demerest had not smiled since he entered the \lquote scaphe. Nor did he really smile now, but a comer of his mouth quirked as he thought that a skinny Moon-man would have no trouble. \par
\tab He went through also, feeling Javan\rquote s hands firmly at his waist, helping him through. \par
\tab Javan said, \ldblquote It\rquote s dark in here. No point in introducing an additional weakness by wiring for lighting. But that\rquote s why flashlights were invented.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest found himself on a perforated walk, its stainless metallic surface gleaming dully. And through the perforations he could make out the wavering surface of water. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote The chamber hasn\rquote t been emptied.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t do any better, Mr. Demerest. If you\rquote re going to use steam to empty it, you\rquote re left with that steam, and to get the pressures necessary to do the emptying that steam must be compressed to a~ut one-third the density of liquid water. When it condenses, the chamber remains one-third full of water--but it\rquote s water at just one-atmosphere pressure. ... Come on, Mr. Demerest.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab John Bergen\rquote s face wasn\rquote t entirely unknown to Demerest. Recognition was immediate. Bergen, as head of Ocean-Deep for nearly a decade now, was a familiar face on the TV screens of Earth-just as the leaders of Luna City had become familiar. \par
\tab Demerest had seen the head of Ocean-Deep both flat and in three dimensions, in black-and-white and in color. Seeing him in life added little. \par
\tab Like Javan, Bergen was short and thickset; opposite in structure to the traditional ( already traditional?) Lunar pattern of physiology. He was fairer than Javan by a good deal and his face was noticeably asymmetrical, with his somewhat thick nose leaning just a little to the right. \par
\tab He was not handsome. No Moon-man would think he was, but then Bergen smiled and there was a sunniness about it as he held out his large hand. \par
\tab Demerest placed his own thin one within, steeling himself for a hard grip, but it did not come. Bergen took the hand and let it go, then said, \ldblquote I\rquote m glad you\rquote re here. We don\rquote t have much in the way of luxury, nothing that will make our hospitality stand out, we can\rquote t even declare a holiday in your honor--but the spirit is there. Welcome!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Demerest softly. He remained unsmiling now, too. He was facing the enemy and he knew it. Surely Bergen must know it also and, since he did, that smile of his was hypocrisy. \par
\tab And at that moment a clang like metal against metal sounded deafeningly and the chamber shuddered. Demerest leaped back and staggered against the wall. \par
\tab Bergen did not budge. He said quietly, \ldblquote That was the bathyscaphe unhitching and the waterclap of the air lock filling. Javan ought to have warned you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest panted and tried to make his racing heart slow. He said, \ldblquote Javan did warn me. I was caught by surprise anyway.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen said, \ldblquote Well, it won\rquote t happen again for a while. We don\rquote t often have visitors, you know. We\rquote re not equipped for it and so we fight off all kinds of big wheels who think a trip down here would be good for their careers. Politicians of all kinds, chiefly. Your own case is different of course.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Is it? thought Demerest. It had been hard enough to get permission to make the trip down. His superiors back at Luna City had not approved in the first place and had scouted the idea that a diplomatic interchange would be of any use. ( \ldblquote Diplomatic interchange\rdblquote  was what they had called it. ) And when he had overborne them, there had been Ocean-Deep\rquote s own reluctance to receive him. \par
\tab It had been sheer persistence alone that had made his present visit possible. In what way then was Demerest\rquote s case different? \par
\tab Bergen said, \ldblquote I suppose you have your junketing problems on Luna City, too?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very little,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \ldblquote Your average politician isn\rquote t as anxious to travel a half-million-mile round trip as he is to travel a ten-mile one.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I can see that,\rdblquote  agreed Bergen, \ldblquote and it\rquote s more expensive out to the Moon, of course. ...In a way, this is the first meeting of inner and outer space. No Ocean-man has ever gone to the Moon as far as I know and you\rquote re the first Moonman to visit a sub-sea station of any kind. No Moon-man has ever been to one of the settlements on the continental shelf.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a historic meeting, then,\rdblquote  said Demerest, and tried to keep the sarcasm out of his voice. \par
\tab If any leaked through, Bergen showed no sign. He rolled up his sleeves as though to emphasize his attitude of informality (or the fact that they were very busy, so that there would be little time for visitors?) and said, \ldblquote Do you want coffee? I assume you\rquote ve eaten. Would you like to rest before I show you around? Do you want to wash up, for that matter, as they say euphemistically?\rdblquote  \par
\tab For a moment, curiosity stirred in Demerest; yet not entirely aimless curiosity. Everything involving the interface of Ocean-Deep with the outside world could be of importance. He said, \ldblquote How are sanitary facilities handled here?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s cycled mostly; as it is on the Moon, I imagine. We can eject if we want to or have to. Man has a bad record of fouling the environment, but as the only deep-sea station, what we eject does no perceptible damage. Adds organic matter.\rdblquote  He laughed. \par
\tab Demerest filed that away, too. Matter was ejected; there was therefore ejection tubes. Their workings might be of interest and he, as a safety engineer, had a right to be interested. \par
\tab\ldblquote No, he said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t need anything at the moment. If you\rquote re busy--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s all right. We\rquote re always busy, but I\rquote m the least busy, if you see what I mean. Suppose I show you around. We\rquote ve got over fifty units here, each as big as this one, some bigger--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest looked about. Again, as in the \lquote scaphe, there were angles everywhere, but beyond the furnishings and equipment there were signs of the inevitable spherical outer wall. Fifty of them! \par
\tab\ldblquote Built up,\rdblquote  went on Bergen, \ldblquote over a generation of effort. The unit we\rquote re standing in is actually the oldest and there\rquote s been some talk of demolishing and replacing it. Some of the men say we\rquote re ready for second-generation units, but I\rquote m not sure. It would be expensive--everything\rquote s expensive down here--and getting money out of the Planetary Project Council is always a depressing experience.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest felt his nostrils flare involuntarily and a spasm of anger shot through him. It was a thrust; surely. Luna City\rquote s miserable record with the PPC must be well known to Bergen. \par
\tab But Bergen went on, unnoticing. \ldblquote I\rquote m a traditionalist, too--just a little bit. This is the first deep-sea unit ever constructed. The first two people to remain overnight on the floor of an ocean trench slept here with nothing else beyond this bare sphere except for a miserable portable fusion unit to work the escape hatch. I mean the air lock, but we called it the escape hatch to begin with--and just enough controls for the purpose. Reguera and Tremont, those were the men. They never made a second trip to the bottom, either; stayed Topside forever after. Well, well, they served their purpose and both are dead now. And here we are with fifty people and with six months as the usual tour of duty. I\rquote ve spent only two weeks Topside in the last year and a half.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He motioned vigorously to Demerest to follow him, slid open a door which moved evenly into a recess, and took him into the next unit. Demerest paused to examine the opening. There were no seams that he could notice between the adjacent units. \par
\tab Bergen noted the other\rquote s pause and said, \ldblquote When we add on our units, they\rquote re welded under pressure into the equivalent of a single piece of metal and then reinforced. We can\rquote t take chances, as I\rquote m sure you understand, since I have been given to understand that you\rquote re the head safe--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest cut him off. \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote We on the Moon admire your safety record.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen shrugged. \ldblquote We\rquote ve been lucky. Our sympathy, by the way, on the rotten break you fellows had. I mean that fatal--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest cut him off again. \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen, the Moon-man decided, was either a naturally voluble man or else was eager to drown him in words and get rid of him. \par
\tab\ldblquote The units,\rdblquote  said Bergen, \ldblquote are arranged in a highly branched chain-three-dimensional actually. We have a map we can show you, if you\rquote re interested. Most of the end units represent living-sleeping quarters. For privacy, you know. The working units tend to be corridors as well, which is one of the embarrassments of having to live down here. \par
\tab\ldblquote This is our library; part of it, anyway. Not big, but it\rquote s got our records, too, on carefully indexed and computed microfilm, so that for its kind it\rquote s not only the biggest in the world, but the best and the only. And we have a special computer to handle the references to meet our needs exactly. It collects, selects, coordinates, weighs, then gives us the gist. \par
\tab\ldblquote We have another library, too, book films and even some printed volumes. But that\rquote s for amusement.\rdblquote  \par
\tab A voice broke in on Bergen\rquote s cheerful flow. \ldblquote John? May I interrupt?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest started; the voice had come from behind him. Bergen said, \ldblquote Annette! I was going to get you. This is Stephen Demerest of Luna City. Mr. Demerest, may I introduce my wife, Annette?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest had turned. He said stiffly, a little mechanically, \ldblquote I\rquote m pleased to meet you, Mrs. Bergen.\rdblquote  But he was staring at her waistline. \par
\tab Annette Bergen seemed in her early thirties. Her brown hair was combed simply and she wore no makeup. Attractive, not beautiful, Demerest \lquote noted vaguely. But his eyes kept returning to that waistline. \par
\tab She shrugged a little. \ldblquote Yes, I\rquote m pregnant, Mr. Demerest. I\rquote m due in about two months.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Pardon me,\rdblquote  Demerest muttered. \ldblquote So rude of me. ...I didn\rquote t--\rdblquote  He faded off and felt as though the blow had been a physical one. He hadn\rquote t expected women, though he didn\rquote t know why. He \i knew \i0 there would have to be women in Ocean-Deep. And the ferry pilot had said Bergen\rquote s wife was with him. \par
\tab He stammered as he spoke. \ldblquote How many women are there in Ocean-Deep, Mr. Bergen?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nine at the moment,\rdblquote  said Bergen. \ldblquote All wives. We look forward to a time when we can have the normal ratio of one to one, but we still need workers and researchers primarily, and unless women have important qualifications of \i some \i0 sort--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote They all have important qualifications of \i some \i0 sort, dear,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Bergen. \ldblquote You could keep the men for longer duty if--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote My wife,\rdblquote  said Bergen, laughing, \ldblquote is a convinced feminist but is not above using sex as an excuse to enforce equality. I keep telling her that that is the feminine way of doing it and not the feminist way, and she keeps saying-Well, that\rquote s why she\rquote s pregnant. You think it\rquote s love, sex mania, yearning for motherhood? Nothing of the sort. She\rquote s going to have a baby down here to make a philosophical point.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Annette said coolly, \ldblquote Why not? Either this is going to be home for humanity or it isn\rquote t going to be. If it \i is, \i0 then we\rquote re going to have babies here, that\rquote s all. I want a baby born in Ocean-Deep. There are babies born in Luna City, aren\rquote t there, Mr. Demerest?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest took a deep breath. \i\ldblquote I \i0 was born in Luna City, Mrs. Bergen.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And well she knew it, \ldblquote  muttered Bergen. \par
\tab\ldblquote And you are in your late twenties, I think?\rdblquote  she said. \par
\tab\ldblquote I am twenty-nine,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \par
\tab\ldblquote And well she knew that, too,\rdblquote  said Bergen with a short laugh. \ldblquote You can bet she looked up all possible data on you when she heard you were coming.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is quite beside the point,\rdblquote  said Annette. \ldblquote The point is that for twenty-nine years at least children have been born in Luna City and no children have been born in Ocean-Deep.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Luna City, my dear,\rdblquote  said Bergen, \ldblquote is longer-established. It is over half a century old; we are not yet twenty.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Twenty years is quite enough. It takes a baby nine months.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest interposed, \ldblquote Are there any children in Ocean-Deep?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Bergen. \ldblquote No. Someday, though.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In two months, anyway,\rdblquote  said Annette Bergen positively. \par
\par
\tab The tension grew inside Demerest and when they returned to the unit in which he had first met Bergen, he was glad to sit down and accept a cup of coffee. \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll eat soon,\rdblquote  said Bergen matter-of-factly. \ldblquote I hope you don\rquote t mind sitting here meanwhile. As the prime unit, it isn\rquote t used for much except, of course, for the reception of vessels, an item I don\rquote t expect will interrupt us for a while. We can talk, if you wish.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I \i do \i0 wish,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \par
\tab\ldblquote I hope I\rquote m welcome to join in,\rdblquote  said Annette. \par
\tab Demerest looked at her doubtfully, but Bergen said to him, \ldblquote You\rquote ll have to agree. She\rquote s fascinated by you and by Moon-men generally. She thinks they\rquote re--uh\i --you\rquote re \i0 a new breed, and I think that when she\rquote s quite through being a Deep-woman she wants to be a Moon-woman:\rquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I just want to get a word in edgewise, John, and when I get that in, I\rquote d like to hear what Mr. Demerest has to say. What do you think of us, Mr. Demerest?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest said cautiously, \ldblquote I\rquote ve asked to come here, Mrs. Bergen, because I\rquote m a safety engineer. Ocean-Deep has an enviable safety record--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not one fatality in almost twenty years,\rdblquote  said Bergen cheerfully. \ldblquote Only one death by accident in the C-shelf settlements and none in transit by either sub or \lquote scaphe. I wish I could say, though, that this was the result of wisdom and care on our part. We do our best, of course, but the breaks have been with us--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote John,\rdblquote  said Annette, \ldblquote I really wish you\rquote d let Mr. Demerest speak.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As a safety engineer,\rdblquote  said Demerest, \ldblquote I can\rquote t afford to believe in luck and breaks. We cannot stop Moon-quakes or large meteroites out at Luna City, but we are designed to minimize the effects even of those. There are no excuses or there should be none for human failure. We have not avoided that on Luna City; our record recently has been\rdblquote --his voice dropped--\rdblquote bad. While humans are imperfect, as we all know, machinery should be designed to take that imperfection into account. We lost twenty men and women--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I know. Still, Luna City has a population of nearly one thousand, doesn\rquote t it? Your survival isn\rquote t in danger.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The people on Luna City number nine hundred and seventy-two, including myself, but our survival \i is \i0 in danger. We depend on Earth for essentials. That need not always be so; it wouldn\rquote t be so right now if the Planetary Project Council could resist the temptation toward pygmy economies--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There, at least, Mr. Demerest,\rdblquote  said Bergen, \ldblquote we see eye to eye. We are not self-supporting either, and we could be. What\rquote s more, we can\rquote t grow much beyond our present level unless nuclear \lquote scaphes are built. As long as we keep that buoyancy principle, we are limited. Transportation between Deep and Top is slow; slow for men; slower still for materiel and supplies. I\rquote ve been pushing, Mr. Demerest, for--\ldblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, and you\rquote ll be getting it now, Mr. Bergen, won\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I hope so, but what makes you so sure?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Mr. Bergen, let\rquote s not play around. You know very well that Earth is committed to spending a fixed amount of money on expansion projects-on programs designed to expand the human habitat-and that it is not a terribly large amount. Earth\rquote s population is not going to lavish resources in an effort to expand either outer space or inner space if it thinks this will cut into the comfort and convenience of Earth\rquote s prime habitat, the land surface of the planet.\rdblquote  Annette broke in. \ldblquote You make it sound callous of Earthmen, Mr. Demerest, and that\rquote s unfair.. It\rquote s only human, isn\rquote t it, to want to be secure? Earth is overpopulated and it is only slowly reversing the havoc inflicted on the planet by the Mad Twentieth. Surely man\rquote s original home must come first, ahead of either Luna City or Ocean-Deep. Heavens, Ocean-Deep is almost \i home \i0 to me, but I can\rquote t want to see it flourish at the expense of Earth\rquote s land.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s not an either-or, Mrs. Bergen,\rdblquote  said Demerest earnestly. \ldblquote If the ocean and outer space are firmly, honestly, and intelligently exploited, it can only redound to Earth\rquote s benefit. A small investment will be lost but a large one will redeem itself with profit.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen held up his hand. \ldblquote Yes, I know. You don\rquote t have to argue with me on that point. You\rquote d be trying to convert the converted. Come, let\rquote s eat. I tell you what. We\rquote ll eat here. If you\rquote ll stay with us overnight, or several days for that matter-you\rquote re quite welcome-there will be ample time to meet everybody. Perhaps you\rquote d rather take it easy for a while, though.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Much rather,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \ldblquote Actually, I want to stay here\'85I would like to ask, by the way, why I met so few people when we went through the units.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No mystery,\rdblquote  said Bergen genially. \ldblquote At any given time, some fifteen of our men are asleep and perhaps fifteen more are watching films or playing chess or, if their wives are with them--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, John,\rdblquote  said Annette. \par
\tab\ldblquote --And it\rquote s customary not to disturb them. The quarters are constricted and what privacy a man can have is cherished. A few are out at sea; three right now, I think. That leaves a dozen or so at work in here and you met them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll get lunch,\rdblquote  said Annette, rising. \par
\tab She smiled and stepped through the door, which closed automatically behind her. \par
\tab Bergen looked after her. \ldblquote That\rquote s a concession. She\rquote s playing woman for your sake. Ordinarily, it would be just as likely for me to get the lunch. The choice is not defined by sex but by the striking of random lightning.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest said, \ldblquote The doors between units, it seems to me, are of dangerously limited strength.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are they?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If an accident happened, and one unit was punctured--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No meteorites down here,\rdblquote  said Bergen, smiling. \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh yes, wrong word. If there were a leak of any sort, for any reason, then could a unit or a group of units be sealed off against the full pressure of the ocean?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You mean, in the way that Luna City can have its component units automatically sealed off in case of meteorite puncture in order to limit damage to a single unit.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Demerest with a faint bitterness. \ldblquote As did \i not \i0 happen recently.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In theory, we could do that, but the chances of accident are much less down here. As I said, there are no meteorites and, what\rquote s more, there are no currents to speak of. Even an earthquake centered immediately below us would not be damaging since we make no fixed or solid contact with the ground beneath and are cushioned by the ocean itself against the shocks. So we can afford to gamble on no massive influx.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yet if one happened?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then we could be helpless. You see, it is not so easy to seal off component units here. On the Moon, there is a pressure differentia] of just one atmosphere; one atmosphere inside and the zero atmosphere of vacuum outside. A thin seal is enough. Here at Ocean-Deep the pressure differential is roughly a thousand atmospheres. To secure absolute safety against that differentia] would take a great deal of money and you know what you said about getting money out of PPC. So we gamble and so far we\rquote ve been lucky.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And we haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \par
\tab Bergen looked uncomfortable, but Annette distracted both by coming in with lunch at this moment. \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote I hope, Mr. Demerest, that you\rquote re prepared for Spartan fare. All our food in Ocean-Deep is prepackaged and requires only heating. We specialize in blandness and nonsurprise here, and the non-surprise of the day is a bland chicken a la king, with carrots, boiled potatoes, a piece of something that looks like a brownie for dessert, and, of course, all the coffee you can drink. \ldblquote  \par
\tab Demerest rose to take his tray and tried to smile. \ldblquote It sounds very like Moon fare, Mrs. Bergen, and I was brought up on that. We grow our own micro-organismic food. It is patriotic to eat that but not particularly enjoyable. We hope to keep improving it, though.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sure you \i will \i0 improve it... \par
\tab Demerest said, as he ate with a slow and methodical chewing, \ldblquote I hate to ride my specialty, but how secure are you against mishaps in your air-lock entry?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It \i is \i0 the weakest point of Ocean-Deep,\rdblquote  said Bergen. He had finished eating, well ahead of the other two, and was half through with his first cup of coffee. \ldblquote But there\rquote s got to be an interface, right? The entry is as automatic as we can make it and as fail-safe. Number one: there has to be contact at every point about the outer lock before the fusion generator begins to heat the water within the lock. What\rquote s more, the contact has to be metallic and of a metal with just the magnetic permeability we use on our \lquote scaphes. Presumably a rock or some mythical deep-sea monster might drop down and make contact at just the right places; but if so, nothing happens. \par
\tab\ldblquote Then, too, the outer door doesn\rquote t open until the steam has pushed the water out and then condensed; in other words, not till both pressure and temperature have dropped below a certain point. At the moment the outer door begins to open, a relatively slight increase in internal pressure, as by water entry, will close it again.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest said, \ldblquote But then, once men have passed through the lock, the inner door closes behind them and sea water must be allowed into the lock again. Can you do that gradually against the full pressure of the ocean outside?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not very.\rdblquote  Bergen smiled. \ldblquote It doesn\rquote t pay to fight the ocean too hard. You have to roll with the punch. We slow it down to about one-tenth free entry but even so it comes in like a rifle shot-louder, a thunderclap, or waterclap, if you prefer. The inner door can hold it, though, and it is not subjected to the strain very often. Well, wait, you heard the waterclap when we first met, when Javan\rquote s \lquote scaphe took off again. Remember?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I remember,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \ldblquote But here is something I don\rquote t understand. You keep the lock filled with ocean at high pressure at all times to keep the outer door without strain. But that keeps the inner door at full strain. Somewhere there has to be strain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, indeed. But if the outer door, with a thousand-atmosphere differential on its two sides, breaks down, the full ocean in all its millions of cubic miles tries to enter and that would be the end of all. If the inner door is the one under strain and it gives, then it will be messy indeed, but the only water that enters Ocean-Deep will be the very limited quantity in the lock and its pressure will drop at once. We will have plenty of time for repair, for the outer door will certainly hold a long time.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But if both go simultaneously--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then we are through.\rdblquote  Bergen shrugged. \ldblquote I need not tell you that neither absolute certainty nor absolute safety exists. You have to live with some risk and the chance of double and simultaneous failure is so microscopically small that it can be lived with easily.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If all your mechanical contrivances fail--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They fail safe,\rdblquote  said Bergen stubbornly. \par
\tab Demerest nodded. He finished the last of his chicken. Mrs. Bergen was already beginning to clean up. \ldblquote You\rquote ll pardon my questions, Mr. Bergen, I hope.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re welcome to ask. I wasn\rquote t informed, actually, as to the precise nature of your mission here. \lquote Fact finding\rquote  is a weasel phrase. However, I assume there is keen distress on the Moon over the recent disaster and as safety engineer you rightly feel the responsibility of correcting whatever shortcomings exist and would be interested in learning, if possible, from the system used in Ocean-Deep.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly. But, see here, if all your automatic contrivances fail safe for some reason, for any reason, you would be alive, but all your escape-hatch mechanisms would be sealed permanently shut. You would be trapped inside Ocean-Deep and would exchange a slow death for a fast one.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s not likely to happen but we\rquote d \i hope \i0 we could make repairs before our air supply gave out. Besides we \i do \i0 have a manual backup system.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Certainly. When Ocean-Deep was first established and this was the only unit-the one we\rquote re sitting in now-manual controls were all we had. \i That \i0 was unsafe, if you like. There they are, right behind you--covered with friable plastic.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In emergency, break glass,\rdblquote  muttered Demerest, inspecting the covered setup. \par
\tab\ldblquote Pardon me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just a phrase commonly used in ancient fire-fighting systems ...Well, do the manuals still work, or has the system been covered with your friable plastic for twenty years to the point where it has all decayed into uselessness with no one noticing?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. It\rquote s periodically checked, as all our equipment is. That\rquote s not my job personally, but I know it is done. If any electrical or electronic circuit is out of its normal working condition, lights flash, signals sound, everything happens but a nuclear blast. , ..You know, Mr. Demerest, we are as curious about Luna City as you are about Ocean-Deep. I presume you would be willing to invite one of our young men--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How about a young woman?\rdblquote  interposed Annette at once. \par
\tab\ldblquote I am sure you mean yourself, dear,\rdblquote  said Bergen, \ldblquote to which \par
\tab I can only answer that you are determined to have a baby here and to keep it here for a period of time after birth, and that effectively eliminates you from consideration.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest said stiffly, \ldblquote We hope you will send men to Luna City. We are anxious to have you understand our problems.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, a mutual exchange of problems and of weeping on each other\rquote s shoulders might be of great comfort to all. For instance, you have one advantage on Luna City that I wish we could have. With low gravity and a low pressure differential, you can make your caverns take on any irregular and angular fashion that appeals to your aesthetic sense or is required for convenience. Down here we\rquote re restricted to the sphere, at least for the foreseeable future, and our designers develop a hatred for the spherical that surpasses belief. Actually it isn\rquote t funny. It breaks them down. They eventually resign rather than continue to work spherically.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen shook his head and leaned his chair back against a microfilm cabinet. \ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  he continued, \ldblquote when William Beebe built the first deep-set chamber in history in the 1930s--it was just a gondola suspended from a mother ship by a half-mile cable, with no buoyancy chambers and no engines, and if the cable broke, good night, only it never did. ...Anyway, what was I saying? Oh, when Beebe built his first deep-sea chamber, he was going to make it cylindrical; you know, so a man would fit in it comfortably. After all, a man is essentially a tall, skinny cylinder. However, a friend of his argued him out of that and into a sphere on the very sensible grounds that a sphere would resist pressure more efficiently than any other possible shape. You know who that friend was?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, I\rquote m afraid I don\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The man who was President of the United States at the time of Beebe\rquote s descents-Franklin D. Roosevelt. All these spheres you see down here are the great-grandchildren of Roosevelt\rquote s suggestion.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest considered that briefly but made no comment. He returned to the earlier topic. \ldblquote We would particularly like someone from Ocean-Deep,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote to visit Luna City because it might lead to a great enough understanding of the need, on Ocean-Deep\rquote s part, for a course of action that might involve considerable self-sacrifice.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh?\rdblquote  Bergen\rquote s chair came down flat-leggedly on all fours. \ldblquote How\rquote s that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ocean-Deep is a marvelous achievement; I wish to detract nothing from that. I can see where it will become greater still, a wonder of the world. \i Still--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Still?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Still, the oceans are only a part of the Earth; a major part, but only a part. The deep sea is only part of the ocean. It is inner space indeed; it works inward, narrowing constantly to a point.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I think,\rdblquote  broke in Annette, looking rather grim, \ldblquote that you\rquote re about to make a comparison with Luna City.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed I am,\rdblquote  said Demerest. \ldblquote Luna City represents outer space, widening to infinity. There is nowhere to go down here in the long run; everywhere to go out there.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We don\rquote t judge by size and volume alone, Mr. Demerest,\rdblquote  said Bergen. \ldblquote The ocean is only a small part of Earth, true, but for that very reason it is intimately connected with over five billion human beings. Ocean-Deep is experimental but the settlements on the continental shelf already deserve the name of cities. Ocean-Deep offers mankind the chance of exploiting the whole planet--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of polluting the whole planet,\rdblquote  broke in Demerest excitedly. \ldblquote Of raping it, of ending it. The concentration of human effort to Earth itself is unhealthy and even fatal if it isn\rquote t balanced by a turning outward to the frontier.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There is nothing at the frontier,\rdblquote  said Annette, snapping out the words. \ldblquote The Moon is dead, all the other worlds out there are dead. If there are live worlds among the stars, light-years away, they can\rquote t be reached. This ocean is \i living.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote The Moon is living, too, Mrs. Bergen, and if Ocean-Deep allows it, the Moon will become an independent world. We Moon-men will then see to it that other worlds are reached and made alive and, if mankind but has patience, we will reach the stars. We! We! It is only we Moon-men, used to space, used to a world in a cavern, used to an engineered environment, who could endure life in a spaceship that may have to travel centuries to reach the stars.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Wait, wait, Demerest,\rdblquote  said Bergen, holding up his hand.  \ldblquote Back up! What do you mean, if Ocean-Deep allows it? What have we to do with it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re competing with us, Mr. Bergen. The Planetary Project Commission will swing your way, give you more, give us less, because in the short term, as your wife says, the ocean is alive and the Moon, except for a thousand men, is not; because you are a half-dozen miles away and we a quarter of a million; because you can be reached in an hour and we only in three days. And because you have an ideal safety record and we have had-misfortunes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The last, surely, is trivial. Accidents can happen any time, anywhere.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But the trivial can be used,\rdblquote  said Demerest angrily. \ldblquote It can be made to manipulate emotions. To people who don\rquote t see the purpose and the importance of space exploration, the death of Moon-men in ,accidents is proof enough that the Moon is dangerous, that its colonization is a useless fantasy. Why not? It\rquote s their excuse for saving money and they can then salve their consciences by investing part of it in Ocean-Deep instead. That\rquote s why I said the accident on the Moon had threatened the survival of Luna City even though it killed only twenty people out of nearly a thousand.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t accept your argument. There has been enough money for both for a score of years.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not enough money. That\rquote s exactly it. Not enough investment to make the Moon self-supporting in all these years, and then they use that lack of self-support against us. Not enough investment to make Ocean-Deep self-supporting either. ... But now they can give you enough if they cut us out altogether.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you think that will happen?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m almost sure it will, unless Ocean-Deep shows a statesmanlike concern for man\rquote s future.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By refusing to accept additional funds. By not competing with Luna City. By putting the good of the whole race ahead of self-interest.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Surely you don\rquote t expect us to dismantle--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You won\rquote t have to. Don\rquote t you see? Join us in explaining that Luna City is essential, that space exploration is the hope of mankind; that you will wait, retrench, if necessary.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen looked at his wife and raised his eyebrows. She shook her head angrily. Bergen said, \ldblquote You have a rather romantic view of the PPC, I think. Even if I made noble, self-sacrificing speeches, who\rquote s to say they would listen? There\rquote s a great deal more involved in the matter of Ocean-Deep than my opinion and my statements. There are economic considerations and public feeling. Why don\rquote t you relax, Mr. Demerest? Luna City won\rquote t come to an end. You\rquote ll receive funds, I\rquote m sure of it. I tell you, I\rquote m sure of it. Now let\rquote s break this up\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No, I\rquote ve got to convince you one way or another that I\rquote m serious. If necessary, Ocean-Deep must come to a halt unless the PPC can supply ample funds for both.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen said, \ldblquote Is this some sort of official mission, Mr. Demerest? Are you speaking for Luna City officially, or just for yourself?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Just for myself, but maybe that\rquote s enough, Mr. Bergen.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t think it is. I\rquote m sorry, but this is turning out to be unpleasant. I suggest that, after all, you had better return Topside on the first available \lquote scaphe.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not yet! Not yet!\rdblquote  Demerest looked about wildly, then rose unsteadily and put his back against the wall. He was a little too tall for the room and he became conscious of life receding. One more step and he would have gone too far to back out. \par
\tab He had told them back on the Moon that there would be no use talking, no use negotiating. It was dog-eat-dog for the available funds and Luna City\rquote s destiny must not be aborted; not for Ocean-Deep; not -for Earth; no, not for all of Earth, since mankind and the Universe came even before the Earth. Man must outgrow his womb and\par
\tab Demerest could hear his own ragged breathing and the inner turmoil of his whirling thoughts. The other two were looking at him with what seemed concern. Annette rose and said, \ldblquote Are you ill, Mr. Demerest?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am \i not \i0 ill. Sit down. I\rquote m a safety engineer and I want to teach you about safety. Sit \i down, \i0 Mrs. Bergen.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Sit down, Annette,\rdblquote  said Bergen. \ldblquote I\rquote ll take care of him.\rdblquote  He rose and took a step forward. \par
\tab But Demerest said, \ldblquote No. Don\rquote t you move either. I have something right here. You\rquote re too naive concerning human dangers, Mr. Bergen. You guard against the sea and against mechanical failure and you don\rquote t search your human visitors, do you? I have a weapon, Bergen.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Now that it was out and he had taken the final step, from which there was no returning, for he was now dead whatever he did, he was quite calm. \par
\tab Annette said, \ldblquote Oh, John,\rdblquote  and grasped her husband\rquote s arm. \ldblquote He\rquote s--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen stepped in front of her. \ldblquote A weapon? Is that what that thing is? Now slowly, Demerest, slowly. There\rquote s nothing to get hot over. If you want to talk, we will talk. What is that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing dramatic. A portable laser beam.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But what do you want to do with it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Destroy Ocean-Deep.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you can\rquote t, Demerest. You know you can\rquote t. There\rquote s only so much energy you can pack into your fist and any laser you can hold can\rquote t pump enough heat to penetrate the walls.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I know that. This packs more energy than you think. It\rquote s Moon-made and there are some advantages to manufacturing the energy unit in a vacuum. But you\rquote re right. Even so, it\rquote s designed only for small jobs and requires frequent recharging. So I don\rquote t intend to try to cut through a foot-plus of alloy steel. ...But it will do the job indirectly. For one thing, it will keep you two quiet. There\rquote s enough energy in my fist to kill two people.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You wouldn\rquote t kill us,\rdblquote  said Bergen evenly. \ldblquote You have no reason.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If by that,\rdblquote  said Demerest, \ldblquote you imply that I am an unreasoning being to be somehow made to understand my madness, forget it. I have every reason to kill you and I \i will \i0 kill you. By laser beam if I have to, though I would rather not.\rdblquote  . \par
\tab\ldblquote What good will killing us do you? Make me understand. Is it that I have refused to sacrifice Ocean-Deep funds? I couldn\rquote t do anything else. I\rquote m not really the one to make the decision. And if you kill me, that won\rquote t help you force the decision in your direction, will it? In fact, quite the contrary. If a Moon-man is a murderer, how will that reflect on Luna City? Consider human emotions on Earth.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was just an edge of shrillness in Annette\rquote s voice as she joined in. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you see there will be people who will say that Solar radiation on the Moon has dangerous effects? That the genetic engineering which has reorganized your bones and muscles has affected mental stability? Consider the word \lquote lunatic,\rquote  Mr. Demerest. Men once believed the Moon brought madness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am not mad, Mrs. Bergen.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter,\rdblquote  said Bergen, following his wife\rquote s lead smoothly. \ldblquote Men will say that you were; that all Moon-men are; and Luna City will be closed down and the Moon itself closed to all further exploration, perhaps forever. Is that what you want?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That might happen if they thought I killed you, but they won\rquote t. It will be an accident.\rdblquote  With his left elbow, Demerest broke the plastic that covered the manual controls. \par
\tab\ldblquote I know units of this sort,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I know exactly how it works. Logically, breaking that plastic should set up a warning flash--after all, it might be broken by accident--and then someone would be here to investigate, or, better yet, the controls should lock until deliberately released to make sure the break w~ not merely accidental.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He paused, then said, \ldblquote But I\rquote m sure no one will come; that no warning has taken place. Your manual system is not failsafe because in your heart you were sure it would never be used.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What do you plan to do?\rdblquote  said Bergen. \par
\tab He was tense and Demerest watched his knees carefully, and said, \ldblquote If you try to jump toward me, I\rquote ll shoot at once, and then keep right on with what I\rquote m doing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I think maybe you\rquote re giving me nothing to lose.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote ll lose time. Let me go right on without interference and you\rquote ll have some minutes to keep on talking. You may even be able to talk me out of it. There\rquote s my proposal. Don\rquote t interfere with me and I will give you your chance to argue.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But what do you plan to do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This,\rdblquote  said Demerest. He did not have to look. His left hand snaked out and closed a contact. \ldblquote The fusion unit will now pump heat into the air lock and the steam will empty it. It will take a few minutes. When it\rquote s done, I\rquote m sure one of those little red-glass buttons will light.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are you going to--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest said, \ldblquote Why do you ask? You know that I must be intending, having gone this far, to Rood Ocean-Deep?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But why? Damn it, why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because it will be marked down as an accident. Because your safety record will be spoiled. Because it will be a complete catastrophe and will wipe you out. And PPC will then turn from you, and the glamor of Ocean-Deep will be gone. \i We \i0 will get the funds; \i we \i0 will continue. If I could bring that to pass in some other way, I would, but the needs of Luna City are the needs of mankind and those are paramount.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You will die, too,\rdblquote  Annette managed to say. \par
\tab\ldblquote Of course. Once I am forced to do something like this, would I \i want \i0 to live? I\rquote m not a murderer.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you will be. If you flood this unit, you will flood all of Ocean-Deep and kill everyone in it--and doom those who are out in their subs to slower death. Fifty men and women --an unborn child--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is not my fault,\rdblquote  said Demerest, in clear pain. \ldblquote I did not expect to find a pregnant woman here, but now that I have, I can\rquote t stop because of that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you must stop,\rdblquote  said Bergen. \ldblquote Your plan won\rquote t work unless what happens can be shown to be an accident. They\rquote ll find you with a beam emitter in your hand and with the manual controls clearly tampered with. Do you think they won\rquote t deduce the truth from that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest was feeling very tired. \ldblquote Mr. Bergen, you sound desperate. Listen-When the outer door opens, water under a thousand atmospheres of pressure will enter. It will be a massive battering ram that will destroy and mangle everything in its path. The walls of the Ocean-Deep units will remain but everything inside will be twisted beyond recognition. Human beings will be mangled into shredded tissue and splintered bone and death will be instantaneous and unfelt. Even if I were to burn you to death with the laser there would be nothing left to show it had been done, so I won\rquote t hesitate, you see. This manual unit will be smashed anyway; anything I can do will be erased by the water .\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But the beam emitter, the laser gun. Even damaged, it will be recognizable,\rdblquote  said Annette. \par
\tab\ldblquote We use such things on the Moon, Mrs. Bergen. It is a common tool; it is the optical analogue of a jackknife. I could kill you with a jackknife, you know, but one would not deduce that a man carrying a jackknife, or even holding one with the blade open, was necessarily planning murder. He might be whittling. Besides, a Moon-made laser is not a projectile gun. It doesn\rquote t have to withstand .an internal explosion. It is made of thin metal, mechanically weak. After it is smashed by the waterclap I doubt that it will make much sense as an object.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest did not have to think to make these statements. He had worked them out within himself through months of self-debate back on the Moon. \par
\tab\ldblquote In fact,\rdblquote  he went on, \ldblquote how will the investigators ever know what happened in here? They will send \lquote scaphes down to inspect what is left of Ocean-Deep, but how can they get inside without first pumping the water out? They will, in effect, have to build a new Ocean-Deep and that would take--how long? Perhaps, given public reluctance to waste money, they might never do it at all and content themselves with dropping a laurel wreath on the dead walls of the dead Ocean-Deep.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen said, \ldblquote The men on Luna City will know what you have done. Surely one of them will have a conscience. The truth will be known.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote One truth,\rdblquote  said Demerest, \ldblquote is that I am not a fool. No one on Luna City knows what I planned to do or will suspect what I have done. They sent me down here to negotiate cooperation on the matter of financial grants. I was to argue and nothing more. There\rquote s not even a laser-beam emitter missing up there. I put this one together myself out of scrapped parts. ...And it works. I\rquote ve tested it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Annette said slowly, \ldblquote You haven\rquote t thought it through. Do you know what you\rquote re doing?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve thought it through. I know what I\rquote m doing. ...And I know also that you are both conscious of the lit signal. I\rquote m aware of it. The air lock is empty and time\rquote s up, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Rapidly, holding his beam emitter tensely high, he closed another contact. A circular part of the unit wall cracked into a thin crescent and rolled smoothly away. \par
\tab Out of the corner of his eye, Demerest saw the gaping darkness, but he did not look. A dankly salt vapor issued from it; a queer odor of dead steam. He even imagined he could: hear the flopping sound of the gathered water at the bottom of the lock. \par
\tab Demerest said, \ldblquote In a rational manual unit, the outer door ought to be frozen shut now. With the inner door open, nothing ought to make the outer door open. I suspect, though, that the manuals were put together too quickly at first for that precaution to have been taken, and it was replaced too quickly for that precaution to have been added. And if I need further evidence of that, you wouldn\rquote t be sitting there so tensely if you knew the outer door wouldn\rquote t open. I need touch one more contact and the waterclap will come. We will feel nothing. \ldblquote  \par
\tab Annette said, \ldblquote Don\rquote t push it just yet. I have one more thing to say. You said we would have time to persuade you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote While the water was being pushed out.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just let me say this. A minute. A \i minute. \i0 I said you didn\rquote t know what you were doing. You don\rquote t. You\rquote re destroying the space program, the \i space \i0 program. There\rquote s more to space than \i space.\rdblquote  \i0 Her voice had grown shrill. \par
\tab Demerest frowned. \ldblquote What are you talking about? Make sense, or I\rquote ll end it all. I\rquote m tired. I\rquote m frightened. I want it over.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Annette said, \ldblquote You\rquote re not in the inner councils of the PPC. Neither is my husband. But I am. Do you think because I am a woman that I\rquote m secondary here? I\rquote m not. You, Mr. Demerest, have your eyes fixed on Luna City only. My husband has his fixed on Ocean-Deep. Neither of you know \i anything. \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Where do you expect to go, Mr. Demerest, if you had all the money you wanted? Mars? The asteroids? The satellites of the gas giants? These are all small worlds; all dry surfaces under a blank sky. It may be generations before we are ready to try for the stars and till then we\rquote d have only pygmy real estate. Is that your ambition? \par
\tab\ldblquote My husband\rquote s ambition is no better. He dreams of pushing man\rquote s habitat over the ocean Boor, a surface not much larger in the last analysis than the surface of the Moon and the other pygmy worlds. We of the PPC, on the other hand, want more than either of you, and if you push that button, Mr. Demerest, the greatest dream mankind has ever had will come to nothing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Demerest found himself interested despite himself, but he said, \ldblquote You\rquote re just babbling.\rdblquote  It was possible, he knew, that somehow they had warned others in Ocean-Deep, that any moment someone would come to interrupt, someone would try to shoot him down. He was, however, staring at the only opening, and he had only to close one contact, without even looking, in a second\rquote s movement. \par
\tab Annette said, \ldblquote I\rquote m not babbling. You know it took more than rocket ships to colonize the Moon. To make a successful colony possible, men had .to be altered genetically and adjusted to low gravity. You are a product of such genetic engineering.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well ?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And might not genetic engineering also help men to greater gravitational pull? What is the largest planet of the Solar System, Mr. Demerest?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Jupi--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Jupiter. Eleven times the diameter of the Earth; forty times the diameter of the Moon. A surface a hundred and twenty times that of the Earth in area; sixteen hundred times that of the Moon. Conditions so different from anything we can encounter anywhere on the worlds the size of Earth or less that any scientist of any persuasion would give half his life for a chance to observe at close range.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But Jupiter is an impossible target.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed?\rdblquote  said Annette, and even managed a faint smile. \ldblquote As impossible as flying? Why is it impossible? Genetic engineering could design men with stronger and denser bones, stronger and more compact muscles. The same principles that enclose Luna City against the vacuum and Ocean-Deep against the sea can also enclose the future Jupiter-Deep against its ammoniated surroundings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The gravitational field--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can be negotiated by nuclear-powered ships that are now on the drawing board. You don\rquote t know that but I do.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re not even sure about the depth of the atmosphere. The pressures--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The pressures! The \i pressures! \i0 Mr. Demerest, look about you. Why do you suppose Ocean-Deep was \i really \i0 built? To exploit the ocean? The settlements on the continental shelf are doing that quite adequately. To gain knowledge of the deep-sea bottom? We could do that by \lquote scaphe easily and we could then have spared the hundred billion dollars invested in Ocean-Deep so far. \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t you see, Mr. Demerest, that Ocean-Deep must mean something more than that? The purpose\rquote  of Ocean-Deep is to devise the ultimate vessels and mechanisms that will suffice to explore and colonize \i Jupiter. \i0 Look about you and see the beginnings of a Jovian environment; the closest approach we can come to it on Earth. It is only a faint image of mighty Jupiter, but it\rquote s a beginning. \par
\tab\ldblquote Destroy this, Mr. Demerest, and you destroy any hope for Jupiter. On the other hand, let us live and we will, together, penetrate and settle the brightest jewel of the Solar System. And long before we can reach the limits of Jupiter, we will be ready for the stars, for the Earth-type planets circling them, \i and \i0 the Jupiter-type planets, too. Luna City won\rquote t be abandoned because \i both \i0 are necessary for this ultimate aim.\rdblquote  \par
\tab For the moment, Demerest had altogether forgotten about that last button. He said, \ldblquote Nobody on Luna City has heard of this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i\ldblquote You \i0 haven\rquote t. There are those on Luna City who know. If you had told them of your plan of destruction, they would have stopped you. Naturally, we can\rquote t make this common knowledge and only a few people anywhere can know. The public supports only with difficulty the planetary projects now in progress. If the PPC is parsimonious it is because public opinion limits its generosity. What do you suppose public opinion would say if they thought we were aiming toward Jupiter? What a super-boondoggle that would be in their eyes. But we continue and what money we can save and make use of we place in the various facets of Project Big World.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Project Big World?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Annette. \ldblquote You know now and I have committed a serious security breach. But it doesn\rquote t matter, does it? Since we\rquote re all dead and since the project is, too.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Wait. now, Mrs. Bergeh.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If you change your mind now, don\rquote t think you can ever talk about Project Big World. That would end the project just as effectively as destruction here would. And it would end both your career and mine. It might end Luna City and Ocean-Deep, too--so now that you know, maybe it makes no difference anyway. You might just as well push that button.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I said wait--\rdblquote  Demerest\rquote s brow was furrowed and his eyes burned with anguish. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen gathered for the sudden jump as Demerest\rquote s tense alertness wavered into uncertain introspection, but Annette grasped her husband\rquote s sleeve. \par
\tab A timeless interval that might have been ten seconds long followed and then Demerest held out his laser. \ldblquote Take it,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I\rquote ll consider myself under arrest.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t be arrested,\rdblquote  said Annette, \ldblquote without the whole story coming out.\rdblquote  She took the laser and gave it to Bergen. \ldblquote It will be enough that you return to Luna City and keep silent. Till then we will keep you .under guard.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bergen was at the manual controls. The inner door slid shut and after that there was the thunderous waterclap of the water returning into the lock. \par
\par
\tab Husband and wife were alone again. They had not dared say a word until Demerest was safely put to sleep under the watchful eyes of two men detailed for the purpose. The unexpected waterclap had roused everybody and a sharply bowdlerized account of the incident had been given out. \par
\tab The manual controls were now locked off and Bergen said, \ldblquote From this point on, the manuals :will have to be adjusted to fail-safe. And visitors will have to be searched.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, John,\rdblquote  said Annette. \ldblquote I think people are insane. There we were, facing death for us and for Ocean-Deep; just the end of everything. And I kept thinking-1 must keep calm; I mustn\rquote t have a miscarriage.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You kept calm all right. You were magnificent. I mean, Project Big World! I never conceived of such a thing, but by -by\i --Jove, \i0 it\rquote s an attractive thought. It\rquote s wonderful.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry I had to say all that, John. It was all a fake, of course. I made it up, Demerest wanted me to make something up really. He wasn\rquote t a killer or destroyer; he was, according to his own overheated lights, a patriot, and I suppose he was telling himself he must destroy in order to save -a common enough view among the small-minded. But he \i said \i0 he would give us time to talk him out of it and I think he was praying we would manage to do so. He wanted us to think of something that would give him the excuse to save in order to save, and I gave it to him. I\rquote m sorry I had to fool you, John.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You didn\rquote t fool me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How could you? I knew you weren\rquote t a member of PPC.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What made you so sure of that? Because I\rquote m a woman?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. Because \i I\rquote m \i0 a member, Annette, and \i that\rquote s \i0 confidential. And, if you don\rquote t mind, I will begin a move to initiate exactly what you suggested-Project Big World.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well!\rdblquote  Annette considered that and, slowly, smiled. \ldblquote Well! That\rquote s not bad. Women do have their uses.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Something,\rdblquote  said Bergen, smiling also, \ldblquote I have never denied.\rdblquote  \par
