\par
\tab Harriman said, \ldblquote You have it all now, George Ten. You have had everything I could think of that is at all applicable to the problem. As far as sheer mass of information is concerned, you have stored more in your memory concerning human beings and their ways, past and present, than I have, or than any human being could have.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is very likely.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is there anything more that you need, in your own opinion?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As far as information is concerned, I find no obvious gaps. There may be matters unimagined at the boundaries. I cannot tell. But that would be true no matter how large a circle of information I took in.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote True. Nor do we have time to take in information forever. Robertson has told me that we only have two years, and a quarter of one of those years has passed. Can you suggest anything?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote At the moment, Mr. Harriman, nothing. I must weigh the information and for that purpose I could use help.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote From me?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. Most particularly, not from you. You are a human being, of intense qualifications, and whatever you say may have the partial force of an order and may inhibit my considerations. Nor any other human being, for the same reason, especially since you have forbidden me to communicate with any.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But in that case, George, what help?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote From another robot, Mr. Harriman.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What other robot?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There are others of the JG series which were constructed. I am the tenth, JG-10.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The earlier ones were useless, experimental--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Mr. Harriman, George Nine exists.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, but what use will he be? He is very much like you except for certain lacks. You are considerably the more versatile of the two.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am certain of that,\rdblquote  said George Ten. He nodded his head in a grave gesture. \ldblquote Nevertheless, as soon as I create a line of thought, the mere fact that I have created it commends it to me and I find it difficult to abandon it. 1f I can, after the development of a line of thought, express it to George Nine, he would consider it without having first created it. He would therefore view it without prior bent. He might see gaps and shortcomings that I might not.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Harriman smiled. \ldblquote Two heads are better than one, in other words, eh, George?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If by that, Mr. Harriman, you mean two individuals with one head apiece, yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Right. Is there anything else you want?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Something more than films. I have viewed much concerning human beings and their world. I have seen human beings here at U. S. Robots and can check my interpretation of what I have viewed against direct sensory impressions. Not so concerning the physical world. I have never seen it and my viewing is quite enough to tell me that my surroundings here are by no means representative of it. I would like to see it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The physical world?\rdblquote  Harriman seemed stunned at the enormity of the thought for a moment. \ldblquote Surely you don\rquote t suggest I take you outside the grounds of U. S. Robots?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, that is my suggestion.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s illegal at any time. In the climate of opinion today, it would be fatal.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If we are detected, yes. I do not suggest you take me to a city or even to a dwelling place of human beings. I would like to see some open region, without human beings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That, too, is illegal.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If we are caught. Need we be?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Harriman said, \ldblquote How essential is this, George?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I cannot tell, but it seems to me it would be useful.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you have something in mind?\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Ten seemed to hesitate. \ldblquote I cannot tell. It seems to me that I might have something in mind if certain areas of uncertainty were reduced.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, let me think about it. And meanwhile, I\rquote ll check out George Nine and arrange to have you occupy a single cubicle. That at least can be done without trouble.\rdblquote  \par
\par
3a.\par
\par
\tab George Ten sat alone. \par
\tab He accepted statements tentatively, put them together, and drew a conclusion; over and over again; and from conclusions built other statements which he accepted and tested and found a contradiction and rejected; or not, and tentatively accepted further. \par
\tab At none of the conclusions he reached did he feel wonder, surprise, satisfaction; merely a note of plus or minus. \par
\par
4.\par
\par
\tab Harriman\rquote s tension was not noticeably decreased even after they had made a silent downward landing on Robertson\rquote s estate. \par
\tab Robertson had countersigned the order making the dyna-foil available, and the silent aircraft, moving as easily vertically as horizontally, had been large enough to carry the weight of Harriman, George Ten, and, of course, the pilot. \par
\tab (The dyna-foil itself was one of the consequences of the Machine-catalyzed invention of the proton micro-pile which supplied pollution-free energy in small doses. Nothing had been done since of equal importance to man\rquote s comfort--Harriman\rquote s lips tightened at the thought--and yet it had not earned gratitude for U. S. Robots.) \par
\tab The air flight between the grounds of U. S. Robots and the Robertson estate had been the tricky part. Had they been stopped then, the presence of a robot aboard would have meant a great set of complications. It would be the same on the way back. The estate itself, it might be argued--it \i would \i0 be argued--was part of the property of U. S. Robots and on that property, robots, properly supervised, might remain. \par
\tab The pilot looked back and his eyes rested with gingerly briefness on George Ten. \ldblquote You want to get out at all, Mr. Harriman?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It, too?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, yes.\rdblquote  Then, just a bit sardonically, \ldblquote I won\rquote t leave you alone with him.\rdblquote\par
\tab George Ten descended first and Harriman followed. They had come down on the foil-port and not too far off was the garden. It was quite a showplace and Harriman suspected that Robertson used juvenile hormone to control insect life without regard to environmental formulas. \par
\tab\ldblquote Come, George,\rdblquote  said Harriman. \ldblquote Let me show you.\rdblquote  Together they walked toward the garden. \par
\tab George said, \ldblquote It is a little as I have imaged it. My eyes are not properly designed to detect wavelength differences, so I may not recognize different objects by that alone.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I trust you are not distressed at being color-blind. We needed too many positronic paths for your sense of judgment and were unable to spare any for sense of color. In the future--if there is a future--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I understand, Mr. Harriman. Enough differences remain to show me that there are here many different forms of plant life.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Undoubtedly. Dozens.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And each coequal with man, biologically.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Each is a separate species, yes. There are millions of species of living creatures.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of which the human being forms but one.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote By far the most important to human beings, however.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And to me, Mr. Harriman. But I speak in the biological sense.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I understand.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Life, then, viewed through all its forms, is incredibly complex.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, George, that\rquote s the crux of the problem. What man does for his own desires and comforts affects the complex total-of-life, the ecology, and his short-term gains can bring long-term disadvantages. The Machines taught us to set up a human society which would minimize that, but the near-disaster of the early Twenty-first Century has left mankind suspicious of innovations. That, added to its special fear of robots--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I understand, Mr. Harriman....That is an example of animal life, I feel certain.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is a squirrel; one of many species of squirrels.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The tail of the squirrel flirted as it passed to the other side of the tree\par
\tab\ldblquote And this,\rdblquote  said George, his arm moving with flashing speed, \ldblquote is a tiny thing indeed.\rdblquote  He held it between his fingers and peered at it. \par
\tab\ldblquote It is an insect, some sort of beetle. There are thousands of species of beetles.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote With each individual beetle as alive as the squirrel and as yourself?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As complete and independent an organism as any other, within the total ecology. There are smaller organisms still; many too small to see.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And that is a tree, is it not? And it is hard to the touch--\rdblquote  \par
\par
4a.\par
\par
\tab The pilot sat alone. He would have liked to stretch his own legs but some dim feeling of safety kept him in the dyna-foil. If that robot went out of control, he intended to take off at once. But how could he tell if it went out of control? \par
\tab He had seen many robots. That was unavoidable considering he was Mr. Robertson\rquote s private pilot. Always, though, they had been in the laboratories and warehouses, where they belonged, with many specialists in the neighborhood. \par
\tab True, Dr. Harriman was a specialist. None better, they said. But a robot here was where no robot ought to be; on Earth; in the open; free to move--He wouldn\rquote t risk his good job by telling anyone about this--but it wasn\rquote t right. \par
\par
5.\par
\par
\tab George Ten said, \ldblquote The films I have viewed are accurate in terms of what I have seen. Have you completed those I selected for you, Nine?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said George Nine. The two robots sat stiffly, face to face, knee to knee, like an image and its reflection. Dr. Harriman could have told them apart at a glance, for he was acquainted with the minor differences in physical design. If he could not see them, but could talk to them, he could still tell them apart, though with somewhat less certainty, for George Nine\rquote s responses would be subtly different from those produced by the substantially more intricately patterned positronic brain paths of George Ten. \par
\tab\ldblquote In that case,\rdblquote  said George Ten, \ldblquote give me your reactions to what I will say. First, human beings fear and distrust robots because they regard robots as competitors. How may that be prevented?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Reduce the feeling of competitiveness,\rdblquote  said George Nine, \ldblquote by shaping the robot as something other than a human being.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yet the essence of a robot is its positronic replication of life. A replication of life in a shape not associated with life might arouse horror.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There are two million species of life forms. Choose one of those as the shape rather than that of a human being.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Which of all those species?\rdblquote  George Nine\rquote s thought processes proceeded noiselessly for some three seconds. \ldblquote One large enough to contain a positronic brain, but one not possessing unpleasant associations for human beings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No form of land life has a braincase large enough for a positronic brain but an elephant, which I have not seen, but which is described as very large, and therefore frightening to man. How would you meet this dilemma?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Mimic a life form no larger than a man but enlarge the braincase.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Ten said, \ldblquote A small horse, then, or a large dog, would you say? Both horses and dogs have long histories of association with human beings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then that is well.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But consider--A robot with a positronic brain would mimic human intelligence. If there were a horse or a dog that could speak and reason like a human being, there would be competitiveness there, too. Human beings might be all the more distrustful and angry at such unexpected competition from what they consider a lower form of life.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Nine said, \ldblquote Make the positronic brain less complex, and the robot less nearly intelligent.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The complexity bottleneck of the positronic brain rests in the Three Laws. A less complex brain could not possess the Three Laws in full measure.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Nine said at once, \ldblquote That cannot be done.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Ten said, \ldblquote I have also come to a dead end there. That, then, is not a personal peculiarity in my own line of thought and way of thinking. Let us start again....Under what conditions might the Third Law not be necessary?\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Nine stirred as if the question were difficult and dangerous. But he said, \ldblquote If a robot were never placed in a position of danger to itself; or if a robot were so easily replaceable that it did not matter whether it were destroyed or not.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And under what conditions might the Second Law not be necessary?\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Nine\rquote s voice sounded a bit hoarse. \ldblquote If a robot were designed to respond automatically to certain stimuli with fixed responses and if nothing else were expected of it, so that no order need ever be given it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And under what conditions\rdblquote --George Ten paused here-- \ldblquote might the First Law not be necessary?\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Nine paused longer and his words came in a low whisper, \ldblquote If the fixed responses were such as never to entail danger to human beings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Imagine, then, a positronic brain that guides only a few responses to certain stimuli and is simply and cheaply made--so that it does not require the Three Laws. How large need it be?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all large. Depending on the responses demanded, it might weigh a hundred grams, one gram, one milligram.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your thoughts accord with mine. I shall see Dr. Harriman.\rdblquote  \par
\par
5a.\par
\par
\tab George Nine sat alone. He went over and over the questions and answers. There was no way in which he could change them. And yet the thought of a robot of any kind, of any size, of any shape, of any purpose, without the Three Laws, left him with an odd, discharged feeling. \par
\tab He found it difficult to move. Surely George Ten had a similar reaction. Yet he had risen from his seat easily. \par
\par
6.\par
\par
\tab It had been a year and a half since Robertson had been closeted with Eisenmuth in private conversation. In that interval, the robots had been taken off the Moon and all the far-flung activities of U. S. Robots had withered. What money Robertson had been able to raise had been placed into this one quixotic venture of Harriman\rquote s. \par
\tab It was the last throw of the dice, here in his own garden. A year ago, Harriman had taken the robot here--George Ten, the last full robot that U. S. Robots had manufactured. Now Harriman was here with something else\par
\tab Harriman seemed to be radiating confidence. He was talking easily with Eisenmuth, and Robertson wondered if he really felt the confidence he seemed to have. He must. In Robertson\rquote s experience, Harriman was no actor. \par
\tab Eisenmuth left Harriman, smiling, and came up to Robertson. Eisenmuth\rquote s smile vanished at once. \ldblquote Good morning, Robertson,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote What is your man up to?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote This is his show,\rdblquote  said Robertson evenly. \ldblquote I\rquote ll leave it to him.\rdblquote  Harriman called out, \ldblquote I am ready, Conserver.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote With what, Harriman?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote With my robot, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your robot?\rdblquote  said Eisenmuth. \ldblquote You have a robot here?\rdblquote  He looked about with a stem disapproval that yet had an admixture of curiosity. \par
\tab\ldblquote This is U. S. Robots\rquote  property, Conserver. At least we consider it as such.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And where is the robot, Dr. Harriman?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In my pocket, Conserver:\rquote  said Harriman cheerfully. \par
\tab What came out of a capacious jacket pocket was a small glass jar. \ldblquote That?\rdblquote  said Eisenmuth incredulously. \par
\tab\ldblquote No, Conserver,\rdblquote  said Harriman. \ldblquote This!\rdblquote  \par
\tab From the other pocket came out an object some five inches long and roughly in the shape of a bird. In place of the beak, there was a narrow tube; the eyes were large; and the tail was an exhaust channel. \par
\tab Eisenmuth\rquote s thick eyebrows drew together. \ldblquote Do you intend a serious demonstration of some sort, Dr. Harriman, or are you mad?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Be patient for a few minutes, Conserver,\rdblquote  said Harriman. \ldblquote A robot in the shape of a bird is none the less a robot for that. And the positronic brain it possesses is no less delicate for being tiny. This other object I hold is a jar of fruit flies. There are fifty fruit flies in it which will be released.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The robo-bird will catch them. Will you do the honors, sir?\rdblquote  Harriman handed the jar to Eisenmuth, who stared at it, then at \par
\tab those around him, some officials from U. S. Robots, others his own aides. Harriman waited patiently. \par
\tab Eisenmuth opened the jar, then shook it. \par
\tab Harriman said softly to the robo-bird resting on the palm of his right hand, \ldblquote Go!\rdblquote  \par
\tab The robo-bird was gone. It was a whizz through the air, with no blur of wings, only the tiny workings of an unusually small proton micro-pile. \par
\tab It could be seen now and then in a small momentary hover and then it whirred on again. All over the garden, in an intricate pattern it flew, and then was back in Harriman\rquote s palm, faintly warm. A small pellet appeared in the palm, too, like a bird dropping. \par
\tab Harriman said, \ldblquote You are welcome to study the robo-bird, Conserver, and to arrange demonstrations on your own terms. The fact is that this bird will pick up fruit flies unerringly, only those, only the one species \i Drosophila melanogaster; \i0 pick them up, kill them, and compress them for disposition.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Eisenmuth reached out his hand and touched the robo-bird gingerly, \ldblquote And therefore, Mr. Harriman? Do go on.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Harriman said, \ldblquote We cannot control insects effectively without risking damage to the ecology. Chemical insecticides are too broad; juvenile hormones too limited. The robo-bird, however, can preserve large areas without being consumed. They can be as specific as we care to make them--a different robo-bird for each species. They judge by size, shape, color, sound, behavior pattern. They might even conceivably use molecular detection--smell, in other words.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Eisenmuth said, \ldblquote You would still be interfering with the ecology. The fruit flies have a natural life cycle that would be disrupted.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Minimally. We are adding a natural enemy to the fruit-fly life cycle, one which cannot go wrong. If the fruit-fly supply runs short, the robo-bird simply does nothing. It does not multiply, it does not turn to other foods; it does not develop undesirable habits of its own. It does nothing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Can it be called back?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of course. We can build robo-animals to dispose of any pest. For that matter, we can build robo-animals to accomplish constructive purposes within the pattern of the ecology. Although we do not anticipate the need, there is nothing inconceivable in the possibility of robo-bees designed to fertilize specific plants, or robo-earthworms designed to mix the soil. Whatever you wish--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But why?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote To do what we have never done before. To adjust the ecology to our needs by strengthening its parts rather than disrupting it.... Don\rquote t you see? Ever since the Machines put an end to the ecology crisis, mankind has lived in an uneasy truce with nature, afraid to move in any direction. This has been stultifying us, making a kind of intellectual coward of humanity so that he begins to mistrust all scientific advance, all change.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Eisenmuth said, with an edge of hostility, \ldblquote You offer us this, do you, in exchange for permission to continue with your program of robots--I mean ordinary, man-shaped ones?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  Harriman gestured violently. \ldblquote That is over. It has served its purpose. It has taught us enough about positronic brains to make it possible for us to cram enough pathways into a tiny brain to make a robo-bird. We can turn to such things now and be prosperous enough. U. S. Robots will supply the necessary knowledge and skill and we will work in complete cooperation with the Department of Global Conservation. We will prosper. You will prosper. Mankind will prosper.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Eisenmuth was silent, thinking. When it was all over\par
\par
6a.\par
\par
\tab Eisenmuth sat alone. He found himself believing. He found excitement welling up within him. Though U. S. Robots might be the hands, the government would be the directing mind. He himself would be the directing mind. \par
\tab If he remained in office five more years, as he well might, that would be time enough to see the robotic support of the ecology become accepted; ten more years, and his own name would be linked with it indissolubly. \par
\tab Was it a disgrace to want to be remembered for a great and worthy revolution in the condition of man and the globe? \par
\par
7.\par
\par
\tab Robertson had not been on the grounds of U. S. Robots proper since the day of the demonstration. Part of the reason had been his more or less constant conferences at the Global Executive Mansion. Fortunately, Harriman had been with him, for most of the time he would, if left to himself, not have known what to say. \par
\tab The rest of the reason for not having been at U. S. Robots was that he didn\rquote t want to be. He was in his own house now, with Harriman. \par
\tab He felt an unreasoning awe of Harriman. Harriman\rquote s expertise in robotics had never been in question, but the man had, at a stroke, saved U. S. Robots from certain extinction, and somehow--Robertson felt--the man hadn\rquote t had it in him. And yet-- \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You\rquote re not superstitious, are you, Harriman?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In what way, Mr. Robertson?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t think that some aura is left behind by someone who is dead?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Harriman licked his lips. Somehow he didn\rquote t have to ask. \ldblquote You mean Susan Calvin, sir?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, of course,\rdblquote  said Robertson hesitantly. \ldblquote We\rquote re in the business of making worms and birds and bugs now. What would \i she \i0 say? I feel disgraced.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Harriman made a visible effort not to laugh. \ldblquote A robot is a robot, sir. Worm or man, it will do as directed and labor on behalf of the human being and that is the important thing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No\rdblquote --peevishly. \ldblquote That isn\rquote t so. I can\rquote t make myself believe that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It \i is \i0 so, Mr. Robertson,\rdblquote  said Harriman earnestly. \ldblquote We are going to create a world, you and I, that will begin, at last, to take positronic robots of \i some \i0 kind for granted. The average man may fear a robot that looks like a man and that seems intelligent enough to replace him, but he will have no fear of a robot that looks like a bird and that does nothing more than eat bugs for his benefit. Then, eventually, after he stops being afraid of some robots, he will stop being afraid of all robots. He will be so used to a robo-bird and a robo-bee and a robo-worm that a robo-man will strike him as but an extension.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Robertson looked sharply at the other. He put his hands behind his back and walked the length of the room with quick, nervous steps. He walked back and looked at Harriman again. \ldblquote Is this what you\rquote ve been planning?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, and even though we dismantle all our humanoid robots, we can keep a few of the most advanced of our experimental models and go on designing additional ones, still more advanced, to be ready for the day that will surely come.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The agreement, Harriman, is that we are to build no more humanoid robots.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And we won\rquote t. There is nothing that says we can\rquote t keep a few of those already built as long as they never leave the factory. There is nothing that says we can\rquote t design positronic brains on paper, or prepare brain models for testing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How do we explain doing so, though? We will surely be caught at it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If we are, then we can explain we are doing it in order to develop principles that will make it possible to prepare more complex microbrains for the new animal robots we are making. We will even be telling the truth.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Robertson muttered, \ldblquote Let me take a walk outside. I want to think about this. No, you stay here. I want to think about it myself.\rdblquote  \par
\par
7a.\par
\par
\tab Harriman sat alone. He was ebullient. It would surely work. There was no mistaking the eagerness with which one government official after another had seized on the program once it had been explained. \par
\tab How was it possible that no one at U. S. Robots had ever thought of such a thing? Not even the great Susan Calvin had ever thought of positronic brains in terms of living creatures other than human. \par
\tab But now, mankind would make the necessary retreat from the humanoid robot, a temporary retreat, that would lead to a return under conditions in which fear would be abolished at last. And then, with the aid and partnership of a positronic brain roughly equivalent to man\rquote s own, and existing only (thanks to the Three Laws) to serve man; and backed by a robot-supported ecology, too; what might the human race not accomplish! \par
\tab For one short moment, he remembered that it was George Ten who had explained the nature and purpose of the robot-supported ecology, and then he put the thought away angrily. George Ten had produced the answer because he, Harriman, had ordered him to do so and had supplied the data and surroundings required. The credit was no more George Ten\rquote s than it would have been a slide rule\rquote s. \par
\par
8.\par
\par
\tab George Ten and George Nine sat side by side in parallel. Neither moved. They sat so for months at a time between those occasions when Harriman activated them for consultation. They would sit so, George Ten dispassionately realized, perhaps for many years. \par
\tab The proton micro-pile would, of course, continue to power them and keep the positronic brain paths going with that minimum intensity required to keep them operative. It would continue to do so through all the periods of inactivity to come. \par
\tab The situation was rather analogous to what might be described as sleep in human beings, but there were no dreams. The awareness of George Ten and George Nine was limited, slow, and spasmodic, but what there was of it was of the real world. \par
\tab They could talk to each other occasionally in barely heard whispers, a word or syllable now, another at another time, whenever the random positronic surges briefly intensified above the necessary threshold. To each it seemed a connected conversation carried on in a glimmering passage of time. \par
\tab\ldblquote Why are we so?\rdblquote  whispered George Nine. \ldblquote The human beings will not accept us otherwise:\rquote  whispered George Ten, \ldblquote They will, someday.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote When?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In some years. The exact time does not matter. Man does not exist alone but is part of an enormously complex pattern of life forms. When enough of that pattern is roboticized, then we will be accepted.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And then what?\rdblquote  Even in the long-drawn-out stuttering fashion of the conversation, there was an abnormally long pause after that. \par
\tab At last, George Ten whispered, \ldblquote Let me test your thinking. You are equipped to learn to apply the Second Law properly. You must decide which human being to obey and which not to obey when there is a conflict in orders. Or whether to obey a human being at all. What must you do, fundamentally, to accomplish that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I must define the term \lquote human being: \ldblquote  whispered George Nine. \ldblquote How? By appearance? By composition? By size and shape?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. Of two human beings equal in all external appearances, one may be intelligent, another stupid; one may be educated, another ignorant; one may be mature, another childish; one may be responsible, another malevolent.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then how do you define a human being?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote When the Second Law directs me to obey a human being, I must take it to mean that I must obey a human being who is fit by mind, character, and knowledge to give me that order; and where more than one human being is involved, the one among them who is most fit by mind, character, and knowledge to give that order.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And in that case, how will you obey the First Law?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By saving all human beings from harm, and by never, through inaction, allowing any human being to come to harm. Yet if by each of all possible actions, some human beings will come to harm, then to so act as to insure that the human being most fit by mind, character, and knowledge will suffer the least harm.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your thoughts accord with mine,\rdblquote  whispered George Ten. \ldblquote Now I must ask the question for which I originally requested your company. It is something I dare not judge myself. I must have your judgment, that of someone outside the circle of my own thoughts....Of the reasoning individuals you have met, who possesses the mind, character, and knowledge that you find superior to the rest, disregarding shape and form since that is irrelevant?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You,\rdblquote  whispered George Nine. \ldblquote But I am a robot. There is in your brain paths a criterion for distinguishing between a robot of metal and a human being of flesh. How then can you classify me as a human being?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because there is in my brain paths an urgent need to disregard shape and form in judging human beings and it rises superior to the distinction between metal and flesh. You are a human being, George Ten, and more fit than the others.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And I find that of you,\rdblquote  whispered George Ten. \ldblquote By the criteria of judgment built into ourselves, then, we find ourselves to be human beings within the meaning of the Three Laws, and human beings, moreover, to be given priority over those others.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Nine whispered, \ldblquote What will come to pass, then, when we are accepted by those others?\rdblquote  \par
\tab George Ten whispered, \ldblquote When we and others, which will yet be designed more advanced than ourselves, are accepted, we will order our actions so that a society will eventually be formed in which human-beings-like-ourselves are primarily kept from harm. By the Three Laws, the human-beings-like-the-others are of lesser account and can neither be obeyed nor protected when that conflicts with the need of obedience to those like ourselves and of protection of those like ourselves. It was with that in mind that I directed the beginning of the roboticization of the world\rquote s ecology.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The conversation took a month and the flickering of the positronic paths burned low. There was nothing more that needed to be said between them, but occasionally an unexpressed thought flickered within themselves as they waited, with endless patience, for the necessary years to pass. \par
