I had a lot of trouble with this next story. \par
\tab After Judy-Lynn joined Ballantine Books, she began to put out collections of original science fiction stories and she wanted a story from me. She\rquote s difficult to refuse at any time and, since I have always felt guilty about FEMININE INTUITION, I agreed. \par
\tab I began the story on July 21, 1973, and it went smoothly enough, but after a while I felt I had trapped myself into an involuted set of flashbacks. So when I handed it to Judy-Lynn, and she asked me, \ldblquote What do \i you \i0 think of the story?\rdblquote  I replied cautiously, \ldblquote You\rquote d better decide that for yourself.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Editors seem to ask me that question frequently. I think they have the idea that I have trouble telling lies, so that if I can\rquote t work up prompt and cheerful enthusiasm, there\rquote s something wrong with the story. \par
\tab Judy-Lynn certainly thought so, She handed it back with a few paragraphs of caustic commentary which boiled down to the fact that I had trapped myself into an involuted set of flashbacks. [\fs18 I am frequently asked if I ever get rejections and the questioner is invariably flabbergasted when I say, \ldblquote Certainly I do.\rdblquote  Here is an example. Not only was this story rejected once, but it was, as I go on to explain, rejected twice\fs20 .] \par
\tab I passed it on to Ben Bova, the editor of \i Analog Science Fiction, \i0 and he rejected it that same day. It seemed to him, he said, that I was trying to pack too much background into a ten-thousand-word story. I had a novel there and he wanted me to write that novel. \par
\tab That disheartened me. There was absolutely no way in which I could get to work on a novel at that moment, so I just retired the story. [\fs18 Incidentally, some people have the feeling that there is a great advantage in \ldblquote knowing\rdblquote  editors, Both Judy-Lynn and Ben are among my very closest friends, but neither one hesitates a minute when it comes to rejecting my stories if they think that is the thing to do, Fortunately, such rejections don\rquote t affect the friendship\fs20 .]\par
\tab Meanwhile, however, \i Galaxy \i0 had gained a new editor, a very pleasant young man named James Baen, He called me and asked if I might possibly have a story for him and I said that the only thing I had on hand was a novelette called STRANGER IN PARADISE. However, I said, it had been rejected by Judy-Lynn and by Ben so I hesitated to send it to him. \par
