I have on occasion written articles for \i The New York Times Magazine \i0 but my batting average with them is less than .500. \par
\tab Ordinarily that sort of thing would be disheartening and I would get to feel that I didn\rquote t have the range on that particular market and that I ought to concentrate my efforts elsewhere. However, the \i Times \i0 is a special case, and I kept trying. \par
\tab By the fall of 1974, however, I had received three rejections in a row and I made up my mind to turn down the next request for an article that I received from them. That\rquote s not as easy as it sounds, because the request usually comes from Gerald Walker, who is as nice a fellow as was ever invented. \par
\tab When he called, I tried desperately to steel myself to a refusal whatever he said, and then he mentioned the magic phrase \ldblquote science fiction.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A science \i fiction \i0 story?\rdblquote  I said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab\ldblquote For the magazine section?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\rdblquote Yes. We want a four-thousand-word story that looks into the future and has something to say about the relationship between man and machine.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll try,\rdblquote  I said. What else could I do? The chance of hitting the \i Times \i0 with a science fiction story was too interesting to pass up. I began working on the story on November 18, 1974, sent it in. to the \i Times \i0 without any real confidence concerning the outcome, and damned if they didn\rquote t take it. It appeared in the January 5, 1975, issue of the Sunday \i Times \i0 and, as far as I could find out, it was the first piece of fiction the \i Times \i0 had ever commissioned and published. \par
