\tab\b0 The whole world was interested. The whole world could watch. If anyone wanted to know how marty did watch, Multivac could have told them. The great computer Multivac kept track-as it did of everything. \par
\tab Multivac was the judge in this particular case, so coldly objective and purely upright that there was no need of prosecution or defense. There was only the accused, Simon Hines, and the evidence, which consisted, in part, of Ronald Bakst. \par
\tab Bakst watched, of course. In his case, it was compulsory .He would rather it were not. In his tenth decade, he was showing signs of age and his rumpled hair was distinctly gray. \par
\tab Noreen was not watching. She had said at the door, \ldblquote If we had a friend left--\rdblquote  She paused, then added, \ldblquote Which I doubt!\rdblquote  and left. \par
\tab Bakst wondered if she would come back at all, but at the moment, it didn\rquote t matter. \par
\tab Hines had been an incredible idiot to attempt actual action, as though one could think of walking up to a Multivac outlet and smashing it--as though he didn\rquote t know a world-girdling computer, \i the \i0 world-girdling Computer (capital letter, please) with millions of robots at its command, couldn\rquote t protect itself. And even if the outlet had been smashed, what would that have accomplished? \par
\tab And Hines did it in Bakst\rquote s physical presence, too! \par
\tab He was called precisely on schedule--\rdblquote Ronald Bakst will give evidence now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Multivac\rquote s voice was beautiful, with a beauty that never quite vanished no matter how often it was heard. Its timbre was neither quite male nor, for that matter, female, and it spoke in whatever language its hearer understood best. \par
\tab\ldblquote I am ready to give evidence,\rdblquote  Bakst said. \par
\tab There was no way to say anything but what he had to say. Hines could not avoid conviction. In the days when Hines would have had to face his fellow human beings, he would have been convicted more quickly and less fairly--and would have been punished more crudely. \par
\par
\tab Fifteen days passed, days during which Bakst was quite alone. Physical aloneness was not a difficult thing to envisage in the world of Multivac. Hordes had died in the days of the great catastrophes and it had been the computers that had saved what was left and directed the recovery-and improved their own designs till all were merged into Multivac--and the five million human beings were left on Earth to live in perfect comfort. . \par
\tab But those five million were scattered and the chances of one seeing another outside the immediate circle, except by design, was not great. No one was designing to see Bakst, not even by television. \par
\tab For the time, Bakst could endure the isolation. He buried himself in his chosen way-which happened to be, these last twenty-three years, the designing of mathematical games. Every man and woman on Earth could develop a way of life to self-suit, provided always that Multivac, weighing all of human affairs with perfect skill, did not judge the chosen way to be subtractive to human happiness. \par
\tab But what could be subtractive in mathematical games? It was purely abstract--pleased Bakst--harmed no one else. \par
\tab He did not expect the isolation to continue. The Congress would not isolate him permanently without a trial--a different kind of trial from that which Hines had experienced, of course, one without Multivac\rquote s tyranny of absolute justice. \par
\tab Still, he was relieved when it ended, and pleased that it was Noreen coming back that ended it. She came trudging over the hill toward him and he started toward her, smiling. It had been a successful five-year period during which they had been together. Even the occasional meetings with her two children and two grandchildren had been pleasant. \par
\tab He said, \lquote Thank you for being back.\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote I\rquote m not back.\rdblquote  She looked tired. Her brown hair was windblown, her prominent cheeks a trifle rough and sunburned. \par
\tab Bakst pressed the combination for a light lunch and coffee. He knew what she liked. She didn\rquote t stop him, and though she hesitated for a moment, she ate. \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve come to talk to you. The Congress sent me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Congress!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Fifteen men and women--counting me. Self-appointed and helpless.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You didn\rquote t think so when you were a member.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve grown older. I\rquote ve learned,\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote At least you\rquote ve learned to betray your friends.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote There was no betrayal. Hines tried to damage Multivac; a foolish, impossible thing for him to try.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You accused him.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I had to. Multivac knew the facts without my accusation, and without my accusation, I would have been an accessory. Hines would not have gained, but I would have lost.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Without a human witness, Multivac would have suspended sentence,\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not in the case of an anti-Multivac act. This wasn\rquote t a case of illegal parenthood or life--work without permission. I couldn\rquote t take the chance.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So you let Simon be deprived of all work permits for two years,\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He deserved it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A\i  \i0 consoling thought, You may have lost the confidence of the Congress, but you have gained the confidence of Multivac,\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The confidence of Multivac is important in the world as it is, \ldblquote  said Bakst seriously. He was suddenly conscious of not being as tall as Noreen, \par
\tab She looked angry enough to strike him; her lips pressed whitely together, But then she had passed her eightieth birthday-no longer young-the habit of non-violence was too ingrained. ...Except for fools like Hines. \par
\tab\ldblquote Is that all you have to say, then?\rdblquote  she said. \par
\tab\ldblquote There could be a great deal to say, Have you forgotten? Have you all forgotten? Do you remember how it once was? Do you remember the Twentieth Century? We live long now; we live securely now; we live happily now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We live worthlessly now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you want to go back to what the world was like once?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Noreen shook her head violently. \ldblquote Demon tales to frighten us. We have learned our lesson. With the help of Multivac we have come through--but we don\rquote t need that help any longer. Further help will soften us to death. Without Multivac, \i we \i0 will run the robots, \i we \i0 will direct the farms and mines and factories.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How well?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well enough. Better, with practice. We need the stimulation of it in any case or we will all die.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote We have our work, Noreen; whatever work we choose.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Whatever we choose, as long as it\rquote s unimportant, and even that can be taken away at will-as with Hines. And what\rquote s your work, Ron? Mathematical games? Drawing lines on paper? Choosing number combinations?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst\rquote s hand reached out to her, almost pleadingly. \ldblquote That can be important. It is not nonsense. Don\rquote t underestimate--\rdblquote  He paused, yearning to explain but not quite knowing how he could, safely. He said, \ldblquote I\rquote m working on some deep problems in combinatorial analysis based on gene patterns that can be used to--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote To amuse you and a few others. Yes, I\rquote ve heard you talk about your games. You will decide how to move from A to B in a minimum number of steps and that will teach you how to go from womb to grave in a minimum number of risks and we will all thank Multivac as we do so.\rdblquote  \par
\tab She stood up. \ldblquote Ron, you will be tried. I\rquote m sure of it. \i Our \i0 trial. And you will be dropped. Multivac will protect you against physical harm, but you know it will not force us to see you, speak to you, or have anything to do with you. You will find that without the stimulation of human interaction, you will not be able to think--or to play your games. Goodbye.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Noreen! Wait!\rdblquote  \par
\tab She turned at the door. \ldblquote Of course, you will have Multivac. You can talk to Multivac, Ron.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He watched her dwindle as she walked down the road through the parklands kept green, and ecologically healthy, by the unobtrusive labors of quiet, single-minded robots one scarcely ever saw. \par
\tab He thought: Yes, I will have to talk to Multivac. \par
\par
\tab Multivac had no particular home any longer. It was a global presence knit together by wire, optical fiber, and microwave. It had a brain divided into a hundred subsidiaries but acting as one. It had its outlets everywhere and no human being of the five million was far from one. \par
\tab There was time for all of them, since Multivac could speak to all individually at the same time and not lift its mind from the greater problems that concerned it. \par
\tab Bakst had no illusions as to its strength. What was its incredible intricacy but a mathematical game that Bakst had come to understand over a decade ago? He knew the manner in which the connecting links ran from continent to continent in a huge network whose analysis could form the basis of a fascinating game. How do you arrange the network so that the flow of information never jams? How do you arrange the switching points? Prove that no matter what the arrangement, there is always at least one point which, on disconnection\par
\tab Once Bakst had learned the game, he had dropped out of the Congress. What could they do but talk and of what use was that? Multivac indifferently permitted talk of any kind and in any depth precisely because it was unimportant. It was only acts that Multivac prevented, diverted, or punished. \par
\tab And it was Hines\rquote s act that was bringing on the crisis; and before Bakst was ready for it, too. \par
\tab Bakst had to hasten now, and he applied for an interview with Multivac without any degree of confidence in the outcome.\par
\tab Questions could be asked of Multivac at any time. There were nearly a million outlets of the type that had withstood Hines\rquote s sudden attack into which, or near which, one could speak. Multivac would answer. \par
\tab An \i interview \i0 was another matter. It required time; it required privacy; most of all it required Multivac\rquote s judgment that it was necessary. Although Multivac had capacities that not all the world\rquote s problems consumed, it had grown chary, somehow, of its time. Perhaps that was the result of its ever-continuing self-improvement. It was becoming constantly more aware of its own worth and less likely to bear trivialities with patience. \par
\tab Bakst had to depend on Multivac\rquote s good will. His leaving of the Congress, all his actions since, even the bearing of evidence against Mines, had been to gain that good will. Surely it was the key to success in this world. \par
\tab He would have to assume the good will. Having made the application, he at once traveled to the nearest substation by air. Nor did he merely send his image. He wanted to be there in person; somehow he felt his contact with Multivac would be closer in that way. \par
\par
\tab The room was almost as it might be if there were to be a human conference planned over closed multivision. For one flash-by moment, Bakst thought Multivac might assume an imaged human form and join him-the brain made flesh. \par
\tab It did not, of course. There was the soft, whispering chuckle of Multivac\rquote s unceasing operations; something always and forever present in Multivac\rquote s presence; and over it, now, Multivac\rquote s voice. \par
\tab It was not the usual voice of Multivac. It was a still, small voice, beautiful and insinuating, almost in his ear. \par
\tab\ldblquote Good day, Bakst. You are welcome. Your fellow human beings disapprove of you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Multivac always comes to the point, thought Bakst. He said, \ldblquote It does not matter, Multivac. What counts is that I accept your decisions as for the good of the human species. You were designed to do so in the primitive versions of yourself and--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And my self-designs have continued this basic approach. If \i you \i0 understand this, why \i do \i0 so many human beings fail to understand it? I have not yet completed the analysis of that phenomenon.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I have come to you with a problem,\rdblquote  said Bakst. Multivac said, \ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote I have spent a great deal of time on mathematical problems inspired by the study of genes and their combinations. I cannot find the necessary answers and home computerization is of no help.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was an odd clicking and Bakst could not repress a slight shiver at the sudden thought that Multivac might be avoiding a laugh. It was a touch of the human beyond what even he was ready to accept. The voice was in his other ear and Multivac said: \par
\tab\ldblquote There are thousands of different genes in the human cell. Each gene has an average of perhaps fifty variations in existence and uncounted numbers that have never been in existence. If we were to attempt to calculate all possible combinations, the mere listing of them at my fastest speed, if steadily continued, would, in the longest possible lifetime of the Universe, achieve but an infinitesimal fraction of the total.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote A complete listing \i is \i0 not needed. That is the point of my game. Some combinations are more probable than others and by building probability upon probability, we can cut the task enormously. It is the manner of achieving this building of probability upon probability that I ask you to help me with.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It would still take a great deal of my time. How could I justify this to myself?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst hesitated. No use in trying a complicated selling job. With Multivac, a straight line was the shortest distance between two points. . \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote An appropriate gene combination might produce a human being more content to leave decisions to you, more willing to believe in your resolve to make men happy, more anxious to \i be \i0 happy. I cannot find the proper combination, but you might, and with guided genetic engineering--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I see what you mean. It is-good. I will devote some time to it.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\tab Bakst found it difficult to hitch into Noreen\rquote s private wave. length. Three times the connection broke away. He was not surprised. In the last two months, there had been an increasing tendency for technology to slip in minor ways-never for long, never seriously-and he greeted each occasion with a somber pleasure. \par
\tab This time it held. Noreen\rquote s face showed, holographically three-dimensional. It flickered a moment, but it held. \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m returning your call,\rdblquote  said Bakst, dully impersonal. \par
\tab\ldblquote For a while it seemed impossible to get you,\rdblquote  said Noreen. \ldblquote Where have you been?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not hiding. I\rquote m here, in Denver.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why in Denver?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The world is my oyster, Noreen. I may go where I please.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Her face twitched a little. \ldblquote And perhaps find it empty everywhere. We are going to try you, Ron.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Now!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And here?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And here!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Volumes of space flickered into different glitters on either side of Noreen, and further away, and behind. Bakst looked from side to side, counting. There were fourteen, six men, eight women. He knew every one of them. They had been good friends once, not so long ago. \par
\tab To either side and beyond the simulacra was the wild background of Colorado on a pleasant summer day that was heading toward its end. There had been a city here once named Denver. The site still bore the name though it had been cleared, as most of the city sites had been. ...He could count ten robots in sight, doing whatever it was robots did. \par
\tab They were maintaining the ecology, he supposed. He knew no details, but Multivac did, and it kepi fifty million robots allover the Earth in efficient order. \par
\tab Behind Bakst was one of the converging grids of Multivac, almost like a small fortress of self-defense. \par
\tab\ldblquote Why now?\rdblquote  he asked. \ldblquote And why here?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Automatically he turned to Eldred. She was the oldest of them and the one with authority-if a human being could be said to have authority. \par
\tab Eldred\rquote s dark-brown face looked a little weary. The years showed, all six score of them, but her voice was firm and incisive. \ldblquote Because we have the final fact now. Let Noreen tell you. She knows you best.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst\rquote s eyes shifted to Noreen. \ldblquote Of what crime am I accused?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Let us play no games, Ron. There are no crimes under Multivac except to strike for freedom and it is your human crime that you have committed no crime under Multivac. For that we will judge whether any human being alive wants your company any longer, wants to hear your voice, be aware of your presence, or respond to you in any way.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why am I threatened with isolation then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You have betrayed all human beings.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Do you deny that you seek to breed mankind into subservience to Multivac?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ah!\rdblquote  Bakst folded his arms across his chest. \ldblquote You found out quickly, but then you had only to ask Multivac.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Noreen said, \ldblquote Do you deny that you asked for help in the genetic engineering of a strain of humanity designed to accept slavery under Multivac without question?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I suggested the breeding of a more contented humanity. Is this a betrayal?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Eldred intervened. She said, \ldblquote We don\rquote t want your sophistry, Ron. We know it by heart. Don\rquote t tell us once again that Multivac cannot be withstood, that there is no use in struggling, that we have gained security. What you call security, the rest of us call slavery.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote Do you proceed now to judgment, or am I allowed a defense?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You heard Eldred,\rdblquote  said Noreen. \ldblquote We know your defense.\rdblquote  . \par
\tab\ldblquote We all heard Eldred,\rdblquote  said Bakst, \ldblquote but no one has heard me. What she says is my defense is not my defense.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was a silence as the images glanced right and left at each other. Eldred said, \ldblquote Speak!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote I asked Multivac to help me solve a problem in the field of mathematical games. To gain his interest, I pointed out that it was modeled on gene combinations and that a solution might help in designing a gene combination that would leave man no worse off than he is now in any respect and yet breed into him a cheerful acceptance of Multivac\rquote s direction, and acquiescence in his decisions.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So we have said,\rdblquote  said Eldred. \par
\tab\ldblquote It was only on those terms that Multivac would have accepted the task. Such a new breed is clearly desirable for mankind by Multivac\rquote s standards, and by Multivac\rquote s standards he must labor toward it: And the desirability of the end will lure him on to examine greater and greater complications of a problem whose endlessness is beyond what even he can handle. You all witness that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Noreen said, \ldblquote Witness what?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Haven\rquote t you had trouble reaching me? In the last two months, hasn\rquote t each of you noticed small troubles in what has always gone smoothly? ...You are silent. May I accept that as an affirmative?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If so what then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote Multivac has been placing all his spare circuits on the problem. He has been slowly pushing the running of the world toward rather a skimpy minimum of his efforts, since nothing, by his own sense of ethics, must stand in the way of human happiness and there can be no greater increase in that happiness than to accept Multivac.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Noreen said, \ldblquote What does all this mean? There is still enough in Multivac to run the world-and us-and if this is done at less than full efficiency, that would only add temporary discomfort to our slavery. Only temporary, because it won\rquote t last long. Sooner or later, Multivac will decide the problem is insoluble, or will solve it, and in either case, his distraction will end. In the latter case, slavery will become permanent and irrevocable.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But for now he is distracted,\rdblquote  said Bakst, \ldblquote and we can even talk like this-most dangerously-without his noticing. Yet I dare not risk doing so for long, so please understand me quickly. \par
\tab\ldblquote I have another mathematical game-the setting up of networks on the model of Multivac. I have been able to demonstrate that no matter how complicated and redundant the network is, there must be at least one place into which all the currents can funnel under particular circumstances. There will always be the fatal apoplectic stroke if that one place is interefered with, since it will induce overloading elsewhere which will break down and induce overloading elsewhere--and so on indefinitely till all breaks down.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And this is the point. Why else have I come to Denver? And Multivac knows it, too, and this point is guarded electronically and robotically to the extent that it cannot be penetrated.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But Multivac is distracted, and Multivac trusts me. I have labored hard to gain that trust, at the cost of losing all of you, since only with trust is there the possibility of betrayal. If any of you tried to approach this point, Multivac might rouse himself even out of his present distraction. If Multivac were not distracted, he would not allow even me to approach. But he \i is \i0 distracted, and it \i is \i0 I!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst was moving toward the converging grid in a calm saunter, and the fourteen images, keyed to him, moved along as well. The soft susurrations of a busy Multivac center were all about them. \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote Why attack an invulnerable opponent? Make him vulnerable first, and then--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Bakst fought to stay calm, but it all depended on this now. Everything! With a sharp yank, he uncoupled a joint. (If he had only had still more time to make more certain.) \par
\tab He was not stopped--and as he held his breath, he became aware of the ceasing of noise, the ending of whisper, the closing down of Multivac. If, in a moment, that soft noise did not return, then he had had the right key point, and no recovery would be possible. If he were not quickly the focus of approaching robots\par
\tab He turned in the continuing silence. The robots in the distance were working still. None were approaching. \par
\tab Before him, the images of the fourteen men and women of the Congress were still there and each seemed to be stupefied at the sudden enormous thing that had happened. \par
\tab Bakst said, \ldblquote Multivac is shut down, burnt out. It can\rquote t be rebuilt.\rdblquote  He felt almost drunk at the sound of what he was saying. \ldblquote I have worked toward this since I left you. When Hines attacked, I feared there might be other such efforts, that Multivac would double his guard, that even I had to work quickly--I wasn\rquote t sure--\rdblquote  He was gasping, but forced himself steady, and said solemnly, \ldblquote I have given us our freedom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And he paused, aware at last of the gathering weight of the silence. Fourteen images stared at him, without any of them offering a word in response. \par
\tab Bakst said sharply, \ldblquote You have talked of freedom. You \i have \i0 it!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Then, uncertainly, he said, \ldblquote Isn\rquote t that what you want?\rdblquote  \par
\par
