When I first finished the preceding story, or thought I had, I was left dissatisfied. I lay awake till about 2 A.M. trying to figure out what dissatisfied me, and then decided I had not made my point. I got up, quickly wrote down the last three paragraphs of the story as it finally appeared, ending with that horrified question, and then went peacefully to sleep. \par
\tab The next day, I rewrote the last page of the manuscript to include the new ending and when I sent it off to the \i Times, \i0 much as I wanted to make the sale, I indicated where I would be intransigent. \par
\tab\ldblquote Please note,\rdblquote  I wrote, \ldblquote that the ending on an unresolved question is not an accident. It is of the essence. Each reader is going to have to consider the meaning of the question and what answer he himself would give.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The \i Times \i0 asked for some trivial changes and clarifications but did not allow even a whisper of objection to emerge concerning my ending, I am glad to say. \par
\tab My own original title had been \ldblquote Mathematical Games,\rdblquote  by the way, and for a while I considered restoring it in the book version. However, THE LIFE AND TIMES OF MULTIVAC has a swing to it. Besides, a large number of people saw it on the single day during which it was available to the reading public. More people came up to me over the next few weeks to tell me they had read that story than had ever been the case for any other story I had ever written. I don\rquote t want them to think I changed the title in order to lure them into thinking they hadn\rquote t read the story before, so that they might buy this book, so THE LIFE AND TIMES OF MULTIVAC it stays. \par
\par
