\b0 The next story has rather a sad history, though I myself emerged unscathed. Here\rquote s how it goes. \par
\tab In January 1975, Naomi Gordon, a very charming woman from Philadelphia, visited me and explained what I thought was a delightful idea for an anthology. It was to be entitled \i The Bicentennial Man; \i0 It was to contain ten stories by top authors, with each one built about that phrase; and it was to be published in connection with the Bicentennial. The well known science fiction enthusiast Forrest J. Ackerman was to do the editing. Naomi also had rather grandiose notions of preparing a very limited, very expensive edition. \par
\tab I pointed out it would be difficult to write science fiction if the stories were to be centered on the Bicentennial, but Naomi said that the stories could be anything at all provided they could be seen to have arisen out of the phrase \ldblquote The Bicentennial Man.\rdblquote  \par
\tab I was intrigued and agreed to do it. I was handed half the advance at once. The deadline was April 1, 1975, and by March 14 I was finished. I was a little rueful about the story at first, for the agreement had called for a 7,500-word story and I had been unable to stop it before it had reached 15,000 --the longest story I had written below the level of a novel in seventeen years. I write an apologetic covering letter, assuring Naomi that there would be no extra charge and she wrote back to say the extra wordage would be fine. Pretty soon, the remaining half of the advance arrived. . \par
\tab But then everything went wrong. Naomi was beset by family and medical problems; some writers who it had been hoped would participate, couldn\rquote t; others who promised stories didn\rquote t deliver them; those who did deliver them did not turn out entirely satisfactory products. \par
\tab Of course, I didn\rquote t know anything about this. It never even occurred to me that anything might go wrong. Actually, my only large interest is in \i writing. \i0 Selling is a minor interest, and what happens afterward is of almost no interest. \par
\tab There was, however, Judy-Lynn del Rey and her enormous awareness of everything that goes on in science fiction. She knew that I had written a story for this anthology. \par
\tab\ldblquote How is it,\rdblquote  she asked dangerously, \ldblquote that you wrote a story for that anthology, yet when I ask you for one you\rquote re always too busy?\rdblquote * \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, \ldblquote  I said apologetically, for Judy-Lynn is a frightening creature when she is moved, \ldblquote the idea of the anthology interested me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How about my suggestions about a robot that has to choose between buying its own liberty and improving its -body? I thought you said that was interesting.\rdblquote  \par
\tab At that point, I must have turned approximately as white as talcum powder. A long time before, she \i had \i0 mentioned such things and I had forgotten. I said, \ldblquote Oh, my goodness, I included something of the sort in the story.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i\ldblquote Again?\rdblquote  \i0 she shrieked. \i\ldblquote Again \i0 you\rquote re using my ideas for other people? Let me see that story. Let me see it!\rdblquote  \par
\tab So I brought her a carbon copy the next day and the day after that she called me. She said, \ldblquote I tried hard not to like the story, but I didn\rquote t manage. I want it. Get the story back.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t do that,\rdblquote  I said. \ldblquote I sold it to Naomi and it\rquote s hers. I\rquote ll write you a different story.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote 1\rquote 11 bet you anything you like,\rdblquote  said Judy-Lynn, \ldblquote that that anthology isn\rquote t going to go through. Why don\rquote t you call and ask?\rquote . \par
\tab I called Naomi and, of course, it wasn\rquote t going through. She agreed to send me back the manuscript and grant me permission to sell the story elsewhere, and I sent back the advance she had given me. (After all, she had lost considerable money on the venture, and I didn\rquote t want any of that loss to represent a profit to me.) \par
\tab The story was then transferred to Judy-Lynn, who used it in her anthology of originals entitled \i Stellar Science Fiction \i0 #2, which appeared in February 1976. And I like the story so much myself that I not only am including it here, but am using its title for the book as a whole. \par
