\tab\b0 That the first inventor of a workable time machine was a science fiction enthusiast is by no means a coincidence. It was inevitable. Why else should an otherwise sane physicist even dare track down the various out-of -the-way theories that seemed to point toward maneuverability in time in the very teeth of General Relativity? \par
\tab It took energy, of course. Everything takes energy. But Simeon Weill was prepared to pay the price. Anything (well, almost anything) to make his hidden science-fictional dream come true. \par
\tab The trouble was that there was no way of controlling either the direction or distance through which one was chronologically thrust. It was all the result of random temporal collisions of the harnessed tachyons. Weill could make mice and even rabbits disappear--but future or past, he couldn\rquote t say. One mouse reappeared, so he must have traveled but a short way into the past--and it seemed quite unharmed. The others? Who could tell? \par
\tab He devised an automatic release for the machine. Theoretically, it would reverse the push (whatever the push might be) and bring back the object (from whichever direction and whatever distance it had gone). It didn\rquote t always work, but five rabbits were brought back unharmed. \par
\tab If he could only make the release foolproof, Weill would have tried it himself. He was \i dying \i0 to try it--which was not the proper reaction of a theoretical physicist, but-was the absolute predictable emotion of a crazed s.f. fan who was particularly fond of the space-operish productions of some decades before the present year of 1976. \par
\tab It was inevitable, then, that the accident should happen. On no account would he have stepped between the tempodes with conscious determination. He knew the chances were about two in five he would not return. On the other hand, he was \i dying \i0 to try it, so he tripped over his own big feet and went staggering between those tempodes as a result of total accident. ...But are there really accidents? \par
\tab He might have been hurled into the past or into the future. As 1t happened, he was ,hurled into the past. \par
\tab He might have been hurled uncounted thousands of years into the past or one and a half days. As it happened, he was hurled fifty-one years into the past to a time when the Teapot Dome Scandal was burning brightly but the nation was keeping Cool with Coolidge and knew that nobody in the world could lick Jack Dempsey. \par
\tab But there was something that his theories didn\rquote t tell Weill. He knew what could happen to the particles themselves, but there was no way of predicting what would happen to the relationships between the various particles. And where are relationships more complex than in the brain? \par
\tab So what happened was that as Weill moved backward through time, his mind unreeled. Not all the way, fortunately, since Weill had not yet been conceived in the year before America\rquote s Sesquicentennial, and a brain with less than no development would have been a distinct handicap. \par
\tab It unreeled haltingly, and partially, and clumsily, and when Weill found himself on a park bench not far from his 1976 home in lower Manhattan, where he experimented in dubious symbiosis with New York University, he found himself in the year 1925 with an abysmally aching head and no very clear idea as to what anything was all about. \par
\tab He found himself staring at a man of about forty, hair slicked down, cheekbones prominent, beaky nose, who was sharing the same bench with him. \par
\tab The man looked concerned. He said, \ldblquote Where did you come from? You were not here a moment ago.\rdblquote  He had a distinct Teutonic accent. . \par
\tab Weill wasn\rquote t sure. He couldn\rquote t remember. But one phrase seemed to stick through the chaos within his skull even though he wasn\rquote t sure what it meant. \par
\tab\ldblquote Time machine,\rdblquote  he gasped. \par
\tab The other man stiffened. He said, \ldblquote Do you read pseudoscientific romances?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Weill. \par
\tab\ldblquote Have you read H. G. Wells\rquote s \i The Time Machine?\rdblquote\par
\i0\tab  The repetition of the phrase seemed to soothe Weill a bit. The pain in his head lessened. The name Wells seemed familiar, or was that his own name? No. his own name was Weill. \par
\i\tab\i0\ldblquote Wells?\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I am Weill.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The other man thrust out a hand. \ldblquote I am Hugo Gernsback. I write pseudo-scientific romances at times, but of course, it is not right to say \lquote pseudo.\rquote  That makes it seem there is something fake about it. That is not so. It should be properly written and then it will be scientific fiction. I like to shorten that\rdblquote -his dark eyes gleamed--\rdblquote to scientifiction. \ldblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Weill, trying desperately to collect shattered memories and unwound experiences and getting only moods and impressions. \ldblquote Scientifiction. Better than pseudo. Still not quite--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If done \i well. \i0 Have you read my \lquote Ralph 124C41 +\rquote ?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hugo Gernsback,\rdblquote  said Weill, frowning, \ldblquote Famous--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In a small way,\rdblquote  said the other, nodding his head. \ldblquote I have been publishing magazines on radio and on electrical inventions for years. Have you read \lquote Science and Invention\rquote ?\rdblquote\par
\tab Weill caught the word \ldblquote invention\rdblquote  and somehow that left him on the edge of understanding what he had meant by \ldblquote time machine.\rdblquote  He grew eager and said, \ldblquote Yes, yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And what do you think of the scientifiction that I add in each issuer\rquote  \par
\tab Scientifiction again. The word had a soothing effect on him and yet it was not quite right. Something more--Not quite--\par
\tab He said it, \ldblquote Something more. Not quite--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not quite enough? Yes, I\rquote ve been thinking that. Last year I sent out circulars asking for subscriptions to a magazine to contain nothing but scientifiction. I would call it \i Scientifiction. \i0 The results were very disappointing. How would you explain that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Weill didn\rquote t hear him. He was still concentrating on the word \ldblquote scientifiction,\rdblquote  which didn\rquote t seem quite right, but he couldn\rquote t understand why it didn\rquote t. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote The name is not right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not right for a magazine? Maybe that\rquote s so. I have not thought of a good name; something to catch the eye, to get across just what the reader will get, and what he will want. That is it. If I could get a good name I would start the magazine and not worry about circulars. I would not ask anything. I would simply put it on every newsstand in the United States next spring; that is all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Weill stared at him blankly. \par
\tab The man said, \ldblquote Of course, the stories I want should teach science even as they amuse and excite the reader. They should open to him the vast scope of the future. Airplanes will cross the Atlantic nonstop.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Airplanes?\rdblquote  Weill caught a fugitive vision of a large metal whale, rising on its own exhaust. A moment, and it was gone. He said, \ldblquote Large ones, carrying hundreds of people faster than sound.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of course. Why not? Staying in touch at all times by radio.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Satellites.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  It was the other man\rquote s turn to look puzzled. \par
\tab\ldblquote Radio waves bounce off an artificial satellite in space.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The other man nodded vigorously. \ldblquote I predicted the use of radio waves to detect at a distance in \lquote Ralph 124C41 + .\rquote  Space mirrors? I\rquote ve predicted that. And television, of course. And energy from the atom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Weill was galvanized. Images flashed before his mind\rquote s eye in no suitable order. \ldblquote Atom,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote Yes. Nuclear bombs.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Radium,\rdblquote  said the other man complacently. \par
\tab\ldblquote Plutonium,\rdblquote  said Weill. \par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Plutonium. And nuclear fusion. Imitating the Sun. Nylon and plastics. Pesticides to kill the insects. Computers to kill the problems.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Computers? You mean robots?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Pocket computers,\rdblquote  said Weill enthusiastically. \ldblquote Little things. Hold them in your hand and work out problems. Little radios. Hold them in your hand, too. Cameras take photographs and develop them right in the box. Holographs. Three. dimensional pictures.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The other man said, \ldblquote Do you write scientifiction?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Weill didn\rquote t listen. He kept trying to trap the images. They were growing clearer. \ldblquote Skyscrapers,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Aluminum and glass. Highways. Color television. Man on the Moon. Probes to Jupiter.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Man on the Moon,\rdblquote  said the other man. \ldblquote Jules Verne. Do you read Jules Verne?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Weill shook his head. It was quite clear now. The mind was healing a bit. \ldblquote Stepping down onto the Moon\rquote s surface on television. Everyone watching. And pictures of Mars. No canals on Mars.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No canals on Mars?\rdblquote  said the other man, astonished. \ldblquote They have been seen.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No canals,\rdblquote  said Weill firmly. \ldblquote Volcanoes. The biggest. Canyons the biggest. Transistors, lasers, tachyons. Trap the tachyons. Make them push against time. Move through time. Move through time. A--ma--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Weill\rquote s voice was fading and his outlines trembled. It so happened that the other man looked away at this moment, staring into the blue sky, and muttering, \ldblquote Tachyons? What is he saying?\rdblquote  \par
\tab He was thinking that if a stranger he met casually in the park was so interested in scientifiction, it might be a good sign that it was time for the magazine. And then he remembered he had no name and dismissed the notion regretfully. \par
\tab He looked back in time to hear Weill\rquote s last words, \ldblquote Tachyonic time travel--an--amazing--stor--y--\rdblquote  And he was gone, snapping back to his own time. \par
\par
\tab Hugo Gernsback stared in horror at the place where the man had been. He hadn\rquote t seen him come and now he really hadn\rquote t seen him go. His mind rejected the actual disappearance. How strange a man-his clothes were oddly cut, come to think of it, and his words were wild and whirling. \par
\tab The stranger himself said it-an amazing story. His last words. \par
\tab And then Gemsback muttered the phrase under his breath, \ldblquote Amazing story. \i ...Amazing Stories?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0 A smile tugged at the comers of his mouth. \par
